<TEXT>
us sen alan cranstons attempts to blame 
former banking regulator edwin j gray for the lincoln savings amp 
loan association debacle were met with a harsh 4000word letter of 
reply 
cranston who is seeking reelection is a desperate 
panicstricken office holder gray wrote monday 
the fact that it happened partially on my watch is as much a 
reflection on your failure yes your unwillingness to help me 
obtain the reforms i sent up to the hill he wrote 
never once sen cranston did you lift a finger to help me 
with the statutory reforms your biggiver friends didnt like 
me or my regulations 
cranston spokesman kam kuwata responded gray claimed he could 
do nothing but he only claims that because he did nothing he 
makes pinnochio look like a piker when it comes to lying about his 
involvement in this scandal 
gray headed the federal home loan bank board when san 
franciscobased federal regulators recommended a takeover of 
irvinebased lincoln on may 1 1987 three weeks after cranston and 
four other senators held their second private meeting with 
regulators gray left office on june 30 1987 
cranston who continues to blame gray for investors losses 
said monday he would introduce legislation allowing the government 
to bail out consumers who lost 200 million on junk bonds purchased 
at lincoln branches 
he said that even though it was technically legal regulators 
should never have allowed lincoln to sell the unsecured bonds 
because investors could easily be led to believe they were 
federally insured 
cranston spoke at the latest in a series of news conferences 
intended to deflect blame aimed at him for the failure of lincoln 
the collapse is expected to cost taxpayers more than 2 billion 
aside from any efforts to repay the junk bond holders 
cranston the senate majority whip is one of five senators 
under investigation by the senate ethics committee for intervening 
with regulators on behalf of lincoln and charles h keating jr 
chief of american continental corp of phoenix lincolns parent 
keating and his family contributed 13 million to the senators 
and their causes 
by focusing on the bondholders cranston hopes to disarm one of 
the most personally damaging allegations against him bondholders 
testimony that his intervention for keating made him partly 
responsible for their losses 
