<TEXT>
a military judge on tuesday 
sentenced an air force maintenance worker to seven years in prison 
and a dishonorable discharge for stealing and selling military 
equipment to undercover fbi agents 
staff sgt chris l london enfield conn pleaded guilty to 20 
charges during a courtmartial monday 
london said he stole the 67432 worth of equipment because he 
needed money to pay bills and child support 
its not an excuse he told air force judge lt col linda 
carter im sorry that it ever happened im glad the government 
property has been returned 
london asked the judge for forgiveness and pleaded for a lenient 
sentence saying lengthy confinement would prevent him from being a 
good father to his son 
carter accepted the guilty pleas and said she wanted to view a 
videotape showing transactions between london and the fbi agents 
before deciding on a sentence she deliberated about one hour 
tuesday and returned with her decision that evening 
london who had faced up to 171 years in military prison 
dishonorable discharge and loss of benefits showed no emotion when 
carter read the sentence 
he was charged in october as a result of operation punchout a 
twoyear fbi sting investigation 
the stolen items included 42 automatic life preserver units 
pilot helmets gloves chin straps camouflage clothing and an 
insect head net 
they were taken from hill air force base between 1986 and 1989 
and sold to a mock military surplus store set up by the fbi in 
nearby roy officials said 
government attorney brian newby of travis air force base in 
california told the judge earlier that london deserved to be put in 
prison for 11 years and receive a dishonorable discharge because he 
disgraced the american flag by lining his pockets with money 
we aim high we expect the best newby said we demand 
the best 
however defense attorney capt george horvath of hill air force 
base said london was remorseful and that financial strains led him 
to commit desperate acts 
the property has been returned intact he said allow him 
the chance to learn and grow from this 
he recommended a twoyear jail sentence 
london 26 was among nearly three dozen military and civilian 
personnel charged in the probe which culminated last july in the 
theft of two f16 jet engines from the base 
two air force security guards admitted stealing the engines and 
will be sentenced friday in us district court 
when the sting was first announced last summer us attorney 
dee benson said it could eventually result in indictments gainst 
more than 100 people the investigation targeted military thefts 
from bases in the west and southwest 
</TEXT>
