<TEXT>
president bushs pet legislative project a 
cut in the capital gains tax is in trouble again on capitol hill 
even though congressional support seemed to be building at the end 
of last year 
it ran headon into a proposal by sen daniel patrick moynihan 
dny to cut social security taxes the collision could derail 
the bush measure or at least complicate the process 
senate majority leader george mitchell of maine once called the 
capital gains cut bushs holy grail 
bush has been pushing the reduction with unabated zeal since 
early in his presidential campaign and in fact since he was a 
junior member of the house ways and means committee during the 
1960s 
the tax on capital gains the profit from the sale of stocks 
real estate and other investments was cut during the mid1970s 
but the major tax code overhaul of 1986 boosted the tax to the same 
rate as other income 28 percent or 33 percent depending on tax 
bracket 
bush associates say the president has a deep repugnance for the 
tax stemming from his oil field business background and honed 
perhaps by his own unpleasant brush with the tax as vice president 
when the internal revenue service rejected his attempt to claim a 
deferral 
when bush sold his familys fivebedroom home in houston in 1981 
for 843273 he claimed a tax deferral on his 596101 capital 
gain because he used the money to buy his family vacation home in 
kennebunkport maine 
but the irs ruled in 1984 that bush misused the deferral saying 
it only would have applied if the kennebunkport home was to be the 
new principal family residence the irs socked the bushes 144000 
in back taxes and 54000 in interest 
bush paid up but accused the irs of unfairly singling him out 
white house aides are bracing for a new democratic assault on 
the capital gains cut while trying to figure ways to separate the 
two tax cut issues 
it may be a hard job in a congressional election year although 
just last fall the house voted to cut the capital gains tax to 196 
percent from the current maximum of 33 percent and the senate gave 
the plan majority approval however the measure died for the year 
in a procedural vote in the senate 
we think the moynihan proposal will die of its own weight it 
wont have any effect on capital gains bush spokesman marlin 
fitzwater said tuesday 
however other white house aides privately were far less 
optimistic conceding democratic attempts to link the two tax cuts 
likely would make it harder to win a reduction in the capital gains 
tax rate 
as congress reconvened after its twomonth recess senate 
majority leader mitchell spelled out the party line that will spell 
trouble for the capital gains tax cut 
its obviously embarrassing to the white house to be in the 
position of advocating a huge tax cut for the very highest people 
in the income bracket and at the same time opposing any tax cuts 
for middleincome and working people saying in effect let the 
little people pay but lets cut taxes for the wealthy mitchell 
said 
the white house strategy is to sniff at such reasoning and to 
belittle the moynihan proposal which bush himself calls a 
charade that will lead to either higher taxes in other areas or 
reduced benefits 
they point to a measure introduced by sen ernest f hollings 
dsc for a 5 percent national sales tax to help make up revenue 
that would be lost by the social security tax cut 
still analysts suggest the administrations role will be a 
difficult one the moynihan plan has created some chaos out 
there said norman ornstein of the conservative american 
enterprise institute 
and lawrence chimerine senior economic adviser for the wefa 
group a private economic forecasting service based in bala cynwyd 
pa said moynihans proposal will make it more difficult to pass 
the capital gains tax cut how can you come up with that after 
rejecting a tax cut for the average guy 
</TEXT>
