<TEXT>
only a small portion of federal drug 
enforcement aid goes to the nations cities says the us 
conference of mayors seeking to boost the mayors call for a 
change in the way the government wages its war on drugs 
the study being released today found city governments received 
just 15 percent of the 150 million in federal funds available for 
drug enforcement through the two main grant programs during the 
last fiscal year that amounted to 221 million 
experience to date has shown that only a small percentage of 
federal antidrug funds has actually reached city governments and 
that it has taken a long time for those funds to arrive said j 
thomas cochran executive director of the conference 
the report was prepared for mayors gathering in washington today 
for their threeday annual winter meeting 
president bush will address the bigcity mayors on friday 
marking the first time in a decade a president has appeared before 
the conference of mayors while in office the last was jimmy carter 
in 1980 
the mayors who are overwhelmingly democratic have long 
complained that cities suffered from neglect and cutbacks in 
federal aid under president reagan 
they have complained since enactment of the federal antidrug 
program in 1986 that the governments war on drugs failed to 
provide adequate support directly to cities where most of the drug 
problems are found mayors have urged the federal government to 
make direct grants to cities rather than providing block grants to 
states for distribution 
boston mayor raymond flynn in an interview on the eve of the 
conference said he believed bushs decision to address the mayors 
indicated the administration may be ready to provide more attention 
and money to the cities problems of drugs poverty and 
homelessness 
i sense this time more a sense of urgency by federal officials 
about the condition of the cities more of a concern flynn said 
flynn said urban leaders will be expecting some help as a result 
of the socalled peace dividend the anticipated defense savings 
resulting from the lessening of world tensions 
its not in the best political interest of congressional 
leaders or white house officials to ignore the messages that have 
been coming out of americas cities flynn said 
congressional leaders also will meet with mayors for talks on 
homelessness and drugs one mayor who wont be attending is the 
host washington mayor marion barry who entered a florida 
treatment center monday following his arrest last week on a cocaine 
possession charge 
the conferences study looked at the two grant programs making 
drug enforcement money available to state city and other local 
governments 
under the formula grants program which distributed 1177 
million to the 50 states plus puerto rico and the district of 
columbia in fiscal 1989 28 percent or 336 million went to state 
agencies the conference reported 
another 17 percent 207 million went to antidrug efforts 
that involved more than one government jurisdiction and 16 
percent or 194 million went to counties fifteen percent or 
18 million had not been awarded and only 12 percent or 144 
million went to cities the study said 
the rest about 12 percent was retained by the states for 
administration went to confidential awards or was given to other 
types of agencies the conference said some of the 
multijurisdictional money went to cities but served an area 
beyond the city limits and was not counted in the cities total 
the report said 
the second program awarded 289 million in fiscal 1989 at the 
discretion of the federal bureau of justice assistance according 
to the study 34 percent or 97 million went to nongovernmental 
agencies and 27 percent or 77 million went to cities the 
remainder went to states counties other governments and federal 
agencies 
