<TEXT>
a government survey of health experts and 
advocates for the elderly shows nearunanimous agreement that 
physical and emotional abuse is a problem in americas nursing 
homes and widespread concern that mistreatment often goes 
unreported 
for each of seven types of abuse more individuals thought the 
situation was worsening than believed it was improving according 
to two draft government reports obtained tuesday 
while there are no exact statistics on institutional abuse 
any abuse is unacceptable the reports said 
the costs of abuse are measured in the physical and 
psychological damage incurred by the resident as well as by the 
economic costs of treating the abused resident they said 
both reports from the inspector generals office of the 
department of health and human services were based on a survey of 
228 people in 35 states who work in state and federal government 
nursing homes and advocacy groups the reports are in draft form 
and subject to revision 
no statebystate breakdown was available 
the reports conclude abusereporting systems are inadequate 
followup on complaints is ineffective and state and federal 
oversight to prevent abuse needs strengthening 
the reports also recommend the federal government require better 
training for nurses aides about aging suggest ways to cope with 
stressful situations and promote more research and education on how 
to improve staff stability in nursing homes and control abuse 
medical personnel other patients families and visitors all 
contribute to the problem but nursing home aides and orderlies are 
the biggest abusers according to the reports 
the reports said many things contribute to abuse by nursing home 
workers including low staffing levels high stress inadequate 
training high turnover job frustration belligerent patients low 
wages lack of empathy for the elderly and increasing numbers of 
severely ill residents 
faced with heavier levels of care such as residents with more 
debilitating diseases frustrated staff take out their stress on 
the residents said one unidentified official who participated in 
the survey 
the report divides abuse into seven categories physical abuse 
misuse of restraints verbal or emotional abuse physical neglect 
medical neglect verbal or emotional neglect and improper use of a 
residents personal property 
ninetyfive percent of those surveyed said there were problems 
in all seven areas thirty percent said physical neglect was the 
most prevalent problem 16 percent said verbal and emotional abuse 
and 14 percent selected verbal and emotional neglect 
the reports said most research on abuse of the elderly focuses 
on family members and caregivers at home and suggests 1 percent to 
10 percent of the noninstitutionalized elderly may be abused 
although there is less information about abuse in nursing homes 
one 1988 study found 36 percent of surveyed nurses and nurses aides 
had seen at least one incident of physical abuse in the preceding 
year and 10 percent said they themselves had committed one or more 
physically abusive acts 
the hhs survey found nursing home industry officials often view 
the abuse problem as minor but a significant number of state 
oversight agencies and advocates for nursing home residents see the 
problem as serious 
fiftyone percent of those interviewed believed abuse is only 
sometimes or rarely reported by nursing home staff suggesting many 
cases go unreported each year the reports said 
the reports said workers may not report abuse because they fear 
for their jobs are loyal to other staff members fear retaliation 
fines penalties and bad publicity lack sufficient facts and 
dont recognize less blatant forms of abuse 
the survey also found doctors often fail to report abuse with 
66 percent of those interviewed reporting physicians who attend to 
patients at nursing homes rarely or never report it 
</TEXT>
