<TEXT>
two environmental groups contend a watchdog 
agency created by congress to oversee nuclear weapons plants is 
operating in illegal secrecy 
the chairman of the agency the defense nuclear facilities 
safety board denied the allegation tuesday while a house panel 
chairman said he had urged the board to clarify its rules on public 
participation 
the allegations were leveled by two environmental groups the 
natural resources defense council and the energy research 
foundation which regularly press the energy department to be more 
open about operations of its nuclear arms plants 
the environmental groups announced they will sue the board if it 
does not open its meetings to the public and release records of its 
meetings by feb 14 
the board created by congress in 1988 began operating oct 25 
dan w reicher an attorney for the natural resources defense 
council said the watchdog agency was violating the 1976 sunshine 
act requiring executive branch agencies to hold meetings in public 
and the freedom of information act which requires agencies to 
publish rules on public access to their records 
the board is perpetuating the culture of secrecy it was 
supposed to eradicate at the energy department reicher said 
john conway chairman of the fivemember board said in a 
telephone interview i dont believe weve violated any federal 
laws 
he acknowledged that some of the boards meetings were not open 
to the public adding that we meet every day were a fulltime 
board and we work every day 
it would be impractical conway said to issue advance notice of 
daily meetings and that some discussions would have to be closed to 
the public because they include classified material 
conway said no one had asked to attend the board meetings or to 
review its records 
rep john spratt dsc chairman of a special house panel 
reviewing the nuclear weapons complex said conway assured him 
tuesday that he was committed to running the watchdog board in as 
open and public a way as possible 
spratt said conway had encountered numerous bureaucratic 
obstacles to organizing the boards work in part because of staff 
hiring problems 
in the short term im sympathetic to his plight spratt 
said adding that he urged conway to move quickly to clarify the 
boards rules on open meetings and public access to records 
the board was established by congress in response to growing 
indications that the energy department had hidden or failed to 
uncover many environmental safety and health problems at the arms 
facilities 
