<TEXT>
private energy analysts agree with a new cia 
forecast of a 2fold increase in us dependence on oil imports 
from the persian gulf but they say the increases may be more 
gradual than the spy agency predicts 
william webster director of the central intelligence agency 
told the senate armed services committee on tuesday that us 
reliance on persian gulf oil will more than double in the coming 
few years 
western dependence on persian gulf oil will rise 
dramatically in the next few years webster said adding the gulf 
share of us oil supplies would rise from 10 percent in 1989 to 
roughly 25 percent in a few years he did not mention a precise 
time period and did not elaborate on the import issue 
president bush contends more reliance on the persian gulf will 
undermine us national security because of the risk of a supply 
interruption this argument disputed by many environmentalists and 
members of congress is central to the administrations efforts to 
open more federal lands and waters to oil exploration 
john lichtblau executive director of the petroleum industry 
research foundation in new york said in an interview that 
websters forecast was reasonable if he was projecting to 1995 he 
said its a little bit exaggerated if webster meant the rise to 
25 percent would occur in two or three years 
lichtblau said his organization was projecting persian gulf oil 
will account for between 22 and 23 percent of us supplies by 
1995 he and other analysts tie the increase to growing us oil 
consumption continuing declines in us oil production and 
declining exports by nongulf oil exporters such as britain 
total us oil imports last year rose to 79 million barrels a 
day that was a 10year high and meant 46 percent of us oil 
supplies came from foreign sources according to the american 
petroleum institute an industry trade association 
dillard spriggs president of the consulting firm petroleum 
analysis ltd in new york said in five years time its quite 
likely that the united states will be getting onequarter of its 
oil from the persian gulf but not before then 
thats where its got to come from he said since no major 
new oil fields are scheduled to come into production outside the 
gulf in the next few years 
the energy departments forecasting office does not publish 
projections of us dependence on oil from specific regions of the 
world said w calvin kilgore who directs the office but kilgore 
said he foresees at least a doubling of us reliance on the 
persian gulf over the next five years 
