rapid changes in eastern europe have reduced 
the soviet threat and could lead to the disintegration of the 
military agreement among the warsaw pact nations by the mid1990s 
say bush administration officials 
there can be no doubt that the conventional military 
threat in central europe has declined central intelligence 
agency director william h webster told the senate armed services 
committee tuesday 
the sessions the panels first in a series of hearings on the 
soviet threat to the west will serve as a basis for the 
committees crafting of a defense budget for the fiscal year that 
begins oct 1 
the ties between the eastern bloc nations and moscow have been 
radically altered in the push toward democracy and the kremlin can 
no longer count on those countries to respond automatically to its 
military orders 
in addition the soviet union has been keeping pace with 
president mikhail gorbachevs december 1988 plan to reduce troop 
levels in eastern europe while the soviets economic problems have 
demanded more money normally earmarked for defense 
soviet and warsaw pact strength and capabilities have 
declined webster said the reductions probably lengthen the 
time it would take for the soviets to mobilize for any largescale 
attack in europe 
despite the diminished threat the cia director said the soviet 
union is still modernizing its strategic forces that combined 
with the threats from terrorism illegal drugs uncertainty in 
latin america asia and the middle east and weapons proliferation 
highlights the importance of maintaining a strong us intelligence 
capability 
the comments appeared to be a plea to head off budget cuts for 
the cia and other intelligence agencies whose operations are 
hidden in the defense department budget although the exact figures 
are secret us intelligence reportedly spends 25 billion to 30 
billion a year just less than 10 percent of the defense budget 
the director of the defense intelligence agency told the panel 
he believes the push for freedom in eastern europe will likely 
lead to the phase out of the warsaw pacts collective military 
security role by the middle of the decade 
lt gen harry soyster said a new type of security agreement 
between the eastern bloc nations could emerge 
the rapid turn of events in eastern europe may accelerate the 
removal of soviet forces and may speed the evolution toward such a 
new security order soyster told the committee 
soyster said he believed the soviet union would view a 
largescale offensive against the nato countries with only their 
