<TEXT>
contaminated cheese was the sole source of an 
outbreak of salmonella infection that sickened thousands of people 
in three states last summer according to a state health department 
investigation 
the outbreak which officials say may have affected 15000 
residents of minnesota wisconsin and north dakota was traced to 
mozzarella cheese that was contaminated through poor sanitation 
practices at the nowclosed kasson cheese plant in brillion wis 
the tainted cheese was made into shredded cheese products at 
three other wisconsin plants and one in minnesota said state 
epidemiologist michael osterholm 
investigators believe the cheese probably was heated enough at 
the brillion plant to kill any salmonella present during 
processing osterholm said tuesday 
however there was ample opportunity for contamination of 
finished cheeses from employee handling or contaminated work 
surfaces before the cheese was packaged he said 
osterholm said employees also indicated that sanitation 
practices had deteriorated at the plant last spring as it faced 
financial problems the company filed for protection from creditors 
in bankruptcy court in may he said 
telephone calls to the kasson plant went unanswered tuesday 
a wisconsin official said he was not certain the entire 
salmonella outbreak could be traced to the kasson plant 
it might have been other food on salad bars that made people 
ill said bill hanson of the wisconsin department of agriculture 
trade and consumer protections food division 
the three other wisconsin plants implicated by osterholm in the 
outbreak has passed inspections hanson said they were the 
associated milk producers inc plant in portage marathon cheese in 
marathon and schreiber foods in green bay 
bill coleman director of the dairy and livestock division of 
the minnesota department of agriculture said no contamination was 
found at the pueringer distributors plant in rice minn 
low levels of the two strains of salmonella blamed for the 
outbreak were found in two unopened packages of mozzarella produced 
at the brillion plant osterholm said 
the outbreak involved two relatively uncommon forms of 
salmonella salmonella javiana and salmonella oranienburg 
confirmed cases represent only a fraction of cases that 
occurred according to the report symptoms included diarrhea 
cramps fever nausea and vomiting and most of those who became 
ill would not have seen a doctor or undergone testing officials 
said 
