here are key dates leading to wednesdays decision 
to dissolve the lower house of parliament and hold a general 
election in japan 
1988 
june news of a scandal emerges affecting top leaders of the 
governing liberal democratic party as well as other influential 
people who profited in bargainpriced share deals the recruit 
scandal named after the recruit co conglomerate leads to 
accusations of bribery 
oct 20 a recruit official is arrested on charges of trying to 
bribe an opposition lawmaker to softpedal his investigation of the 
scandal 
nov 16 a list of 26 politicians and government officials who 
received recruit shares is released in parliament embarrassing 
prime minister noboru takeshita and other party leaders who were 
named 
nov 17 the government pushes through parliament its bill to 
impose a 3 percent tax on sales which proves unpopular even though 
coupled with reductions in income taxes and other levies 
dec 9 finance minister kiichi miyazawa resigns after 
repeatedly changing his explanation of an aides recruit stock 
purchases 
1989 
feb 13 recruit co founder hiromasa ezoe is arrested 
april 11 prime minister takeshita acknowledges he received the 
equivalent of more than 1 million in political donations from 
recruit co 
april 25 takeshita announces he will resign and his secretary 
commits suicide a day later 
june 2 foreign minister sousuke uno becomes prime minster and 
promises political reform but inside a week his standing is 
threatened by published allegations he kept paid mistresses 
july 23 an election for half the members of the upper house of 
parliament results in a defeat for the liberal democrats who lose 
their majority in the lesspowerful chamber for the first time in 
34 years uno says he will resign to take responsibility 
aug 10 toshiki kaifu a former education minister with no 
personal power base in the governing party is named prime minster 
the fourth to hold the post since the last lower house election in 
july 1986 when yasuhiro nakasone headed the government 
nov 12 the opposition majority in the upper house passes a 
bill to abolish the unpopular new sales tax it is the first 
instance in 43 years of either house passing legislation opposed by 
the government and the move increases pressure for an early 
election 
nov 24 six separate trials start for 12 defendants in the 
recruit scandal including two members of parliament on bribery 
charges the trials are expected to last through most of 1990 
1990 
jan 818 prime minister kaifu makes a whirlwind tour of 
countries in east and west europe as politicians at home indicate 
that feb 18 will be the date to elect a new lower house of 
parliament 
jan 24 the lower house the more powerful house as it 
chooses the prime minister is dissolved and the election date is 
set for feb 18 
