<TEXT>
the largest dissident alliance today 
pledged a nationwide drive to stop president roh taewoos 
governing party and two opposition parties from joining forces to 
create a single conservative party 
differences were reported today as talks began on how to 
complete the merger officials involved in the negotiations said 
there was disagreement over who should lead the new party which is 
to be inaugurated in may 
the move announced after talks monday between roh and 
opposition leaders kim youngsam and kim jongpil will join the 
governing democratic justice party with the nations no 2 and 3 
opposition groups led by the two kims 
the new party tentatively called the democratic liberal party 
would be the first in koreas modern history formed by ruling and 
opposition parties 
police today said hundreds of officers were mobilized to protect 
the two kims whose homes and offices have been flooded with 
threatening telephone calls since the announcement 
roh says a new broadbased governing party will give the country 
the political stability it has never had but some fear it will 
radicalize the opposition and cause antigovernment violence 
the united national democratic movement the nations umbrella 
dissident organization involving about 200 groups agreed to launch 
a nationwide movement with all democratic forces opposing the 
new party a spokesman said 
the alliance played a key role in months of street protests that 
forced the government to carry out broad reforms in 1987 
the spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
alliance was ready to work with radical students workers and kim 
daejung whose opposition party for peace and democracy will be 
hurt by the merger it called for immediate elections to form a new 
national assembly 
kim daejung has pledged to collect 10 million signatures on 
petitions calling for new elections to block creation of the new 
party 
a 15member working committee was formed today to discuss 
procedures on the merger of rohs party with kim youngsams 
reunification democratic party and kim jongpils new democratic 
republican party 
officials involved said there were differences over how to 
compose the new partys leadership and hierachy 
members of kim youngsams party want their leader to head the 
new party and supervise its affairs while governing party 
officials support a collective leadership controlled by roh the 
officials said 
roh defeated kim youngsam in the 1987 presidential election by 
a narrow margin 
the merger could be a major victory for roh who will be assured 
of a twothirds majority in the oppositioncontrolled national 
assembly but it could cause serious repercussions by isolating the 
party for peace and democracy the nations most radical and 
largest opposition group 
the party controls the underprivileged cholla provinces where 
onefifth of the nations 42 million people live kwangju the 
scene of a civil uprising in 1980 that left 200 people dead by 
official count is the capital of south cholla province 
the merger also could enliven dissident movements and touch off 
a new wave of violent antigovernment demonstrations 
kim daejung has declared a virtual political war against the 
roh government announcing that our party is prepared to make any 
sacrifice to block the oneparty dictatorship 
dissidents and radical students denouncing the new party as an 
attempt by a prous military dictatorship to prolong its power 
also promised to fight 
the planned merger came as a surpise the two centrist 
opposition parties had been discussing a possible merger but few 
expected rohs governing group to join them 
the merger generally is viewed as a result of rohs desire for 
political stability by obtaining a parliamentary majority coupled 
with the two kims ambitions for postroh leadership 
roh steps down in early 1993 at the end of a single fiveyear 
term 
his party has been in an uncomfortable situation since losing 
its parliamentary majority in the 1988 elections for the first time 
in south koreas 40year constitutional history 
observers think rohs dislike of kim daejung swayed him to 
choose the other two kims as his merger partners 
roh as an army general helped former president chun doohwan 
seize power with military backing in an internal coup in 1980 
under the martial law government controlled by roh and chun 
kim daejung was given the death penalty on what he called 
trumpedup sedition charges in 1980 the sentence was later 
commuted to life in prison and the opposition leader was freed a 
few years later under us pressure 
