the cabinet met today for the 
first time this year with an agenda that included the release of 
jailed black leader nelson mandela and the possible unbanning of 
the african national congress 
decisions reached at the meeting will change the face of south 
africa permanently said the sowetan the countrys largest 
blackoriented daily newspaper 
the cabinet traditionally does not announce its decisions 
immediately after its meetings and the outcome of todays session 
might not be known until president fw de klerk gives a speech 
feb 2 at the opening of parliament 
mandela the countrys most popular black leader has been 
jailed since 1962 and is serving a life sentence for helping plan 
the start of the ancs antigovernment sabotage campaign the 
government has confirmed that he will be freed and there is strong 
speculation the release could occur by midfebruary 
his release is one of several conditions which the anc says must 
be met before it enters negotiations on a new political system that 
would extend voting rights to blacks the outlawed movement also 
demands that it be legalized that the state of emergency imposed 
in 1986 be lifted and that the government halt trials and 
executions of political opponents 
government officials have indicated that these conditions could 
be met at least to a large extent leaving the anc with a decision 
as to whether it should join negotiations 
the staterun south african broadcasting corp in a commentary 
today said the anc is being forced to move away from a strategy 
of violence and towards an acceptance of peaceful negotiation 
mandela who has been meeting regularly with government and 
opposition leaders last week submitted the outlines of a peace 
plan to the ancs exiled leadership in lusaka zambia 
details of the plan have not been disclosed the star of 
johannesburg south africas largest daily said today the reason 
for the secrecy was that the plan contains proposals which are 
either extremely sensitive or embarrassing to the anc 
justice minister kobie coetsee one of the cabinet members who 
has met frequently with mandela said tuesday that the 71yearold 
prisoner might be asked at serve as a mediator between the 
government and the anc 
the anc advocates a oneperson onevote system in which the 28 
million blacks would be able to control the government 
de klerk envisions some sort of system in which the 5 million 
whites would retain a veto over major policy decisions 
