<TEXT>
four of the nations biggest defense 
contractors have asked the government to approve a team effort to 
develop the national aerospace plane a futuristic aircraft that 
could go from runway into orbit 
the move would allow the contractors who had been working 
independently on the project since 1985 to get more for our 
money jim schlueter a spokesman for st louisbased mcdonnell 
douglas corp said tuesday 
the other contractors are general dynamics corp the north 
american aircraft and rocketdyne divisions of rockwell 
international corp and the pratt amp whitney division of united 
technologies corp 
theoretically the experimental nasp x30 aerospace plane would 
be capable of flying 25 times the speed of sound and 10 times 
faster and three times higher than existing commercial aircraft 
the companies have created their own designs but have shared 
some research mainly on construction materials a prototype is 
scheduled to be flown in the late 1990s 
the team agreement is subject to approval by the air force nasa 
and the navy 
we dont anticipate any problems because this is consistent 
with the goal of the program said jw stout a spokesman for 
st louisbased general dynamics 
stout said the companies have worked together on researching and 
testing materials for use in the plane finding a material that is 
lightweight and can withstand intense heat is one of the linchpins 
of the planes development 
the team selected barry waldman a veteran of 26 years of 
technical and management experience with rockwell as program 
director 
the announcement ends a heated battle between rocketdyne and 
pratt amp whitney for the contracts to build engines for the plane 
