a suburban high schools program of random drug 
tests on athletes began without protests but with some raising the 
issue of privacy 
it wasnt that bad said megan mulcahey a member of the 
girls basketball team and one of the first group of 14 students 
who willingly underwent urine tests tuesday at homewoodflossmoor 
high school they treated you nice and everything 
amanda levenberg student government president predicts 
opposition will grow as more students are called upon to undergo 
the procedure 
though not a first nationally the program has gotten attention 
because of its scope the school plans eventually to test all 1200 
sports participants among its 2000member student body 
i was expecting a lot more friction from the student body 
people are complying and theyre not complaining said miss 
levenberg 17 i think it wont hit kids until they have to go 
pee in a cup for someone to test them 
miss mulcahey said she considers the tests a violation of 
privacy that unfairly singles out student athletes 
i dont think its fair that just us are being tested she 
said in a telephone interview if theyre going to go ahead and 
have that it should be everyone 
the school board approved the program in september at the 
suggestion of the football coach who suspected drug use by a 
couple of students athletic director ken schultz said 
schultz picked the first students to be tested from those 
involved in such winter sports as swimming basketball wrestling 
and gymnastics and their parents signed consent forms 
the tests detect use of alcohol steroids and several other 
drugs including marijuana and cocaine students wont know when 
they will be tested until their day comes 
students and their parents will be notified of results within 48 
hours said principal charles smith those who test positive must 
see a drug counselor within 48 hours 
students determined by the counselor to be abusers will be 
suspended from sports and required to undergo treatment they will 
be tested again after 30 days and may return to athletics if they 
pass smith said more treatment is ordered for those who dont 
pass 
schultz said the program probably will be expanded to include 
students involved in other extracurricular activities at the 
school whose students come from several upper middleclass 
largely white southwestern suburbs 
school officials say the tests will give kids an incentive to 
reject drugs 
on weekends when they go to the parties and alcohol is 
served these kids can say no because i might be tested next 
week said smith 
