irancontra arms supplier richard secord today 
was sentenced to two years probation for concealing from 
congressional investigators the fact that he paid for a 13800 
security system at oliver norths home 
secord who was enlisted by north to airlift supplies to the 
nicaraguan rebels and assist the reagan administrations secret 
arms shipments to iran has already suffered enough in the scandal 
said us district court judge aubrey robinson 
secord pleaded guilty nov 8 to making a false statement to 
congressional investigators he could have faced up to five years 
in prison and a 250000 fine 
it is my judgment that there has been punishment in this 
case robinson told the retired air force major general 
secords lawyer thomas green told the judge that his clients 
life has been in tatters since october 1986 when one of the 
airplanes in norths aid network was shot down over nicaragua while 
carrying supplies for the rebels 
the shootdown which took place in the last days of a 
congressional ban on military aid to the contras led to the 
exposure of the secret resupply network overseen by north then a 
national security council aide from his offices in the old 
executive office building next to the white house 
