four tv stations in an unprecedented case of 
cooperation preempted two hours of primetime shows to 
simultaneously broadcast an antidrug program picking up at least 
threequarters of the people watching tv 
the locally produced program texas crackdown was shown 
tuesday on all three major network affiliates in the dallasfort 
worth area and one independent station and was accompanied by a 
radio version on three stations 
dallas and fort worth newspapers joined the effort with drug 
quizzes in their tuesday editions and teachers assigned light 
homework so students could watch the show 
many schools planned quizzes and school projects based on the 
program a nonprofit group sponsored an essay contest for 
students based on the program 
wfaa an abc affiliate aired the program with cbs affiliate 
kdfw nbc affiliate kxas and independent kdtx three 
spanishlanguage radio stations kessam kssaam and kssafm 
broadcast the twohour show in spanish 
nielsen ratings showed that 75 percent of the people watching 
television in the dallasfort worth market watched texas 
crackdown on the network affiliates at 9 pm said wfaatv 
president and general manager dave lane 
on a normal viewing night the percentages would be in the 
midto upper 60s for the three network affiliates lane said 
the independent stations ratings were not available in the 
overnight reports he said 
although the programs were sponsored by local hospitals and 
dominos pizza there were no regularly scheduled commercials the 
