democrats who have strong support from big business 
money politics will be a central theme in the opposition 
campaign against the party that has governed japan since 1955 the 
year it was formed 
liberal democratic incumbents in parliaments lower house each 
received either 103000 or 172000 with the smaller sum going to 
wellknown politicians party sources said the total distributed 
was 386 million 
the 270 candidates endorsed so far called at party headquarters 
to pick up brown paper bags bulging with cash 
earlier wednesday prime minister toshiki kaifu dissolved the 
512member lower house in which the liberal democrats held 295 
seats to pave the way for elections 
in july the party lost its majority in the less powerful upper 
house because of an unpopular sales tax and a bribery scandal 
involving senior liberal democratic politicians 
recent public opinion polls show the governing party leading the 
opposition but if the liberal democrats lose next month a 
coalition led by the japan socialist party probably would take over 
after dissolving the lower house kaifu told fellow party 
members it was their duty to restore the peoples confidence in 
the party 
the cabinet met and decided candidates should register and 
campaigning begin feb 3 when the date of the election will be 
announced officially as feb 18 elections are required by july 
when the fouryear term of the lower house expires 
party elders apparently chose the february date to give the new 
parliament time to consider the budget which must be passed by 
april 1 
a statement issued wednesday by the governing party said 
socialist and communist nations around the world are collapsing 
like an avalanche and a victory by the outdated inflexible 
opposition would represent a return to the past 
liberal democrats pledged action on political reform and 
agricultural welfare and land policies 
kaifu said recently that if his party lost he would take 
responsibility apparently meaning he would resign as his 
predecessor sousuke uno did after the election loss in june 
opposition parties condemned the long hold on power by the 
liberal democrats 
intraldp conflicts prevented prime minister kaifu from 
addressing the diet parliament with his policies before 
dissolution the socialists said policy questions by 
opposition party leaders were also blocked 
such actions resulted from arrogant oneparty rule the 
party said and it appealed for unity behind a coalition that 
reflects the national interest and responds to radically shifting 
domestic and foreign affairs 
the komeito clean government and democratic socialist parties 
said they would hold to the center seeking abolition of the sales 
tax improvement in japans standard of living and progress in 
world peace and disarmament 
the japanese trade union confederation which has 8 million 
members said the election centers on the controversial 3 percent 
sales tax 
eishiro saito chairman of the federation of economic 
organizations which represents japans largest corporations said 
the election eould decide japans destiny in the next century 
he said japans miraculous economic growth has been based on 
stable politics championed by the liberal democrats 
