<TEXT>
the health minister has warned that chinas high 
incidence of hereditary diseases disabilities and illiteracy is a 
threat to national development it was reported wednesday 
minister chen minzhang told a conference that china must use 
propaganda education and legislation to improve the quality of its 
11 billion people according to the china youth news and the 
overseas edition of the peoples daily 
chen said china has 51 million people with physical and mental 
disabilities about 5 percent of the population it has 22 million 
sufferers of hereditary diseases and birth defects afflict 13 
percent of babies 
congenital diseases are so serious in some remote areas where 
marriages among close relatives are common that some communities 
have come to be called deaf and mute villages or simpleton 
villages the minister said 
he said 17 percent of children under 14 are classified as being 
of low intelligence 
the nation has more than 200 million illiterates and 
semiliterates onefourth of the worlds total eighty percent of 
the illiterates are women and 40 million children almost all in 
rural areas have quit school 
chen noted that china has made significant progress in some 
areas since the communists came to power in 1949 with the rate of 
mothers dying in childbirth dropping from 150 per 10000 in 1949 to 
5 per 10000 today the infant mortality rate has dropped from 20 
percent to 35 percent 
but chen said the low quality of the population has become a 
heavy millstone around our neck in the journey to catch up with 
international competition and modernize 
he called for legislation to improve the quality of new babies 
but the reports did not say whether he was referring to 
strengthening the nations onechild policy or controversial 
proposals to prevent some women from giving birth 
northwest chinas gansu province in one of the nations most 
impoverished regions in 1988 passed a law prohibiting 
dullwitted and retarded people from having children and 
saying such people could marry only after being sterilized 
the chinese association for the handicapped last spring also 
called for a national law of eugenics to improve population 
quality 
