a free newspaper keyed to the industry of 
washington the federal government will begin daily publication 
oct 1 the papers backers said wednesday 
the washington reporter will be given away to people in the 
federal government politics media lobbyists lawyers and others 
who make up this industry in washington said publisher roger g 
kranz limited newsstand and outoftown distribution are also 
envisioned 
kranz likened the planned mondayfriday newspaper to daily 
variety and the hollywood reporter entertainment trade dailies 
published in hollywood 
theres a lot that goes on there and theres an awful lot 
that goes on here that is undercovered he said 
this will be a trade newspaper for the industry in washington 
not a major metropolitan daily newspaper the publisher said 
the onesection 16page reporter will not cover sports or the 
weather or have a foreign staff he said although he envisions 
supplementing the papers own reporting with wire service stories 
it will be a newsaper for and about people who work here 
inside the beltway he said 
kranz 39 resigned in august as group vice president of the 
national journal where he was in charge of advertising sales 
circulation and manufacturing 
john s prescott jr a former president of the washington post 
and recently retired president of the publications division of 
whitney communications co in new york will be chairman of the 
board 
the editor will be barry sussman who runs an independent public 
opinion polling and consulting company in washington and formerly 
served as an editor with the washington post and united press 
international 
kranz said he and prescott are investors in the paper but 
sussman is not he declined to name other investors 
the publisher said he has raised enough money to keep the paper 
operating for quite a while but he wouldnt say how long the 
reporters firstyear budget is 1245 million 
kranz said that he expects the paper to have a circulation of 
about 30000 and that a prototype will be published late next month 
kranz said the newspaper would have a staff of 100 including 50 
on the editorial staff and he expects to pay salaries competitive 
with those of other news organizations in washington 
he said he has talked with prospective advertisers and there 
is a great deal of interest in having a viable medium reaching a 
very upscale targeted audience 
outside washington he said there will be limited sameday 
distribution to wall street and midtown new york and to shuttle 
terminals in new york boston and washington 
