president najib said wednesday there 
was no sign the soviet union plans to cut massive military and 
economic aid to his marxist government in its war with moslem 
guerrillas 
at a news conference he reiterated a pledge to step down if he 
believed such a move would end the 11yearold civil war with the 
usbacked insurgents 
najib said that despite moscows handsoff response to the 
democratic reforms that have toppled communist governments in 
eastern europe the soviet union appears determined to continue 
helping his country 
we have not seen any sign which might demonstrate the 
unwillingness of the soviet union to fulfill its contractual 
commitment to its south asian neighbor he told foreign 
journalists 
the burly former chief of the nations secret police said his 
government already has carried out the kind of reforms that are 
transforming east bloc nations 
there are great lessons that should be learned by us all from 
the developments there najib said 
flanked by army troops carrying automatic assault rifles he 
responded to written queries submitted in advance and then answered 
questions directly from reporters security personnel frisked all 
of the reporters and searched their belongings 
najib called on the guerrillas to put down their weapons and 
talk peace 
but he added if the opposition launches more attacks our 
response will be stronger and more crushing than ever before 
the major rebel leaders based in neighboring pakistan have 
rejected any talks with najibs government 
they are fighting to topple his ruling peoples democratic party 
of afghanistan and replace it with an islamic regime 
the party seized power in a bloody military coup in 1978 najib 
assumed office in 1986 after former president babrak karmal 
resigned ostensibly for health reasons 
najib originally offered to resign for the sake of peace in 1987 
asked if the offer still stood he said if the need arises 
for stepping down i can assure you that i will sacrifice 
everything for the sake of assuring peace in my country 
an estimated 15 million people have been killed in the war and 
more than 5 million afghans a third of the countrys prewar 
population have fled to refugee camps in pakistan and iran 
soviet troops spent nine years fighting the guerrillas to a 
stalemate before moscow withdrew the last of them in february 1989 
about 100000 soldiers moved into afghanistan on dec 27 1979 
to replace one promoscow government with another and stayed on to 
fight the insurgents 
the guerrillas and many western countries predicted najibs 
government would fall soon after the withdrawal but government 
forces have held their ground they continue to hold afghanistans 
major cities and the guerrillas control most of the rugged 
countryside 
the united states britain and several other countries closed 
their kabul embassies a year ago ahead of an expected fight for the 
capital 
while the insurgents have intermittently attacked with rockets 
najibs government remains firmly in control and france recently 
announced plans to reopen its embassy 
najib said he warmly welcomes the decision 
we reiterate that the republic of afghanistan is ready to 
assure the safety and security of all foreign diplomats he said 
he denied widespread claims that his party and its security 
force known as khad have killed or tortured thousands of 
opponents in the nearly 12yearold rule of the peoples democratic 
party 
the baseless allegations against the party are only a pretext 
for avoiding talks and continuing the war he said 
najib said his formula for peace would begin with a sixmonth 
ceasefire and talks among officials of his government and 
guerrilla leaders he also said he supports the formation of a 
coalition government and elections held under international 
supervision 
