a florida lawyer scheduled to stand trial 
next week on conspiracy charges in the july 1988 kidnapping of a 
missing jackson heiress claims he was not in jackson on the day she 
disappeared 
newton alfred winn 65 said in a court document filed monday 
that he was in his hometown of st petersburg fla on july 26 
1988 at the time police believe annie laurie hearin was kidnapped 
she has not been seen since 
winn is scheduled to go on trial monday in us district court 
in hattiesburg on charges of conspiring to kidnap mailing a 
threatening letter and perjury 
a note found at her home after she was taken told her husband 
robert m hearin to make payments to winn and 11 others who fought 
legal battles with school pictures of mississippi inc which he 
owned 
hearin mailed checks totaling nearly 1 million to the 12 people 
named in the ransom note winn returned his check 
several witnesses may be called to verify winns whereabouts on 
the day of the kidnapping the court document says 
john m colette of jackson winns attorney refused to comment 
tuesday 
the witness list includes joe donahey a clearwater fla 
attorney who has represented winn donahey said tuesday that he 
could not discuss his contact with winn 
any contact i had with mr winn would have been within an 
attorneyclient relationship donahey said 
other than july 26 winn does not provide an alibi for six other 
dates times and places as requested by prosecutors 
the court papers said a federal court regulation calls for a 
response only concerning the time date and place of which the 
alleged offense was committed 
three of the dates in 1988 that are significant to the 
conspiracy charge are april 7 or 8 july 19 and july 25 
neighbors of the hearins testified a man resembling winn was 
seen in the neighborhood before the kidnapping also a 
superintendent for a construction crew working at fondren 
presbyterian church recalled seeing winn looking around the 
neighborhood two blocks from the hearin home 
the three other dates are significant to the charge that winn 
caused a ransom letter to be mailed to mrs hearins home 
aug 5 or 6 1988 at a hotel in deland fla prosecutors said 
winn met a woman there and asked her to mail a letter that arrived 
at the hearin home on aug 15 the letter in mrs hearins 
handwriting said her captors would seal her in a cellar if their 
demands were not met 
a saturday in late august at a planetarium and museum in 
bradenton fla prosecutors say the woman met winn again and 
received the initial 250 of a 500 payment 
feb 18 1989 at a hotel in deland prosecutors said winn paid 
the woman the remaining 250 
