<TEXT>
foreigners may soon have to pay for 
their zimbabwean brides a top law officer said wednesday 
attorney general patrick chinamasa said the hopeful husbands 
would probably have to pay the traditional african bride price 
under proposed changes to laws covering the powers of tribal chiefs 
in this southern arican nation 
the payment known as lobola is usually made in cattle 
cash clothing and household goods and it is recoverable if the 
woman proves to be barren 
in the past whites did not come under the jurisdiction of 
traditional chiefs courts also known as community courts where 
matrimonial issues arise 
most mixed marriages have been conducted in westernstyle 
ceremonies 
under proposed laws however you could well find a white 
person in front of a community court in any dispute over bride 
price chinamasa told legislators 
he was asking the parliament to approve proposals that restore 
some legal powers to chiefs and remove the exemption of foreigners 
from customary law 
chinamasa conceded that in cases where german and danish aid 
workers in rural zimbabwe married local women they could be liable 
for backdated payments 
the laws are expected to come into force later this year 
</TEXT>
