money does make a difference education 
officials told a house subcommittee wednesday as disagreements 
erupted over public school finances that enable some districts to 
spend up to eight times more than others in the same state 
the notion that money does not make a difference is 
preposterous on its face said arthur e wise director of the 
center for the study of the teaching profession at the rand corp 
when the advantaged have the better financed schools and the 
disadvantaged the poorly financed schools america continues to 
provide unequal education to those who most need what school has to 
offer he said 
wise was one of five witnesses at an education and labor 
subcommittee hearing on a bill to require states to equalize 
education spending statewide or face the loss of federal aid 
the committee chairman rep augustus hawkins dcalif who 
introduced the bill tuesday cited statistics from a congressional 
study that found most states spend widely different sums to educate 
children living in different areas illinois new jersey new york 
texas and vermont were said to have the sharpest disparities 
k forbis jordan a professor at arizona state university said 
census bureau data show the levels of revenue disparity among the 
states ranged from 100 to 1 in hawaii to 849 to 1 in new york 
states with spending disparities below twotoone include 
alabama connecticut delaware florida maryland north carolina 
rhode island south carolina and west virginia the common element 
in these states he said is a relatively small number of school 
districts 
states with spending disparities above fourtoone were alaska 
arkansas colorado minnesota montana new york north dakota 
ohio oklahoma texas and vermont the financing systems in 
montana and texas are being challenged 
rep peter smith rvt questioned the accuracy of the 
statistics from the congressional research service saying they 
were radically wrong 
he said the data do not reflect differences among school 
districts such as population and location 
albert kauffman of the mexican american legal defense and 
educational fund in san antonio texas said that in texas where 
the state supreme court recently found the system of financing 
public school education violates the state constitution the 
richest districts pay half the taxes and spend twice as much on 
their students 
