a former pentagon official who helped guide 
and justify the defense buildup of the 1980s said wednesday he now 
favors scrapping the mx and midgetman missiles but pressing ahead 
with star wars research and the stealth bomber 
richard perle a former assistant secretary of defense who was 
among the most adamant backers of the reagan administration defense 
increases said the liberalization of the soviet union and eastern 
europe also means the united states should consider proposing 
deeper weapons cuts in arms control negotiations 
the soviet empire in collapsing perle told the senate armed 
services committee time is on our side said perle a resident 
fellow at the american enterprise institute a think tank on the 
conservative side of the political spectrum 
in response to the lessening threat of the warsaw pact perle 
suggested possibly reducing ground forces and skipping the next 
generation of weapons systems 
i would not proceed with either the midgetman or the rail 
mobile mx the current generation of icbms intercontinental 
ballistic missiles should prove adequate and the next generation 
will benefit from further research and development if it is 
delayed for a few years he said 
the mx is a 10warhead missile already deployed the midgetman 
is a smaller singlewarhead missile being developed 
the administration has recommended putting the 50 mx missiles 
now based in underground silos on rail cars the trains would move 
about during an international crisis and present a hardertohit 
target than silos the midgetman would be placed on special 
offroad trucks for the same reason 
