<TEXT>
the interior department reached agreement with 
environmental groups wednesday on a new plan to strictly enforce 
the nations strip mining laws 
hailed as an unqualified victory for the environment by 
lawyers for conservation associations the agreement is intended to 
make it easier to revoke coal mining permits issued to companies or 
individuals with records of past violations and to block the 
issuing of new permits in such cases 
at the heart of the new enforcement system is the planned 
installation by july 1 of a new computer system with accurate and 
complete information on coal companies and their owners 
the aim is to match permit holders and applicants with past 
violators of the 1977 strip mining law 
the product of more than four months of intense negotiations 
the agreement settles a legal and environmental dispute that began 
nearly a decade ago during james watts controversial tenure as 
secretary of the interior 
manuel lujan the present secretary signed the new agreement in 
exchange for the dropping of legal action against the department by 
save our cumberland mountains an environmental group based in the 
coalmining regions of appalachia 
lujan said the agreement signals a new willingness by the 
federal government to coooperate with environmentalists 
our aim is fair evenhanded enforcement of the surface mining 
law lujan said in a statement 
brent rushforth an attorney who represented the environmental 
group said the agreement should put an end to years of neglect 
by the department of the interior neglect which permitted mine 
operators to routinely violate the law scar the land and pollute 
the water 
but rushforth said the department has made other agreements over 
the years to enforce the strip mining law and has not complied with 
them 
it is now up to the department to live up to the promises 
rushforth said you can be sure well watch them closely 
rushforth said that to comply with the agreement the 
departments office of surface mining reclamation and enforcement 
will most likely use a computer system developed by save our 
cumberland mountains and the national wildlife federation 
the plan for the department spelled out in the agreement has 
these major components 
coalmining permit applications will be run through the 
computer system with approval given only to those applicants with 
no ties to violators 
a computer review of existing mining permits will be initiated 
and enforcement action taken if a permit was improperly issued 
development by march 1 1990 of a plan to enforce federal 
mining cessation orders 
development of sanctions against people who intentionally give 
incomplete or false ownership information on coalmine permit 
applications 
the surface mining control and reclamation act of 1977 was 
intended to ensure that land stripmined for coal would be restored 
save our cumberland mountains originally sued the department in 
1981 contending the surface mining act was not being enforced 
an initial settlement was reached the next year but rushforth 
said little or nothing was done to implement it 
the environmental group complained that in appalachia in 
particular shell companies have been used to evade the 
requirements of the act with an operator mining a site then 
abandoning it unreclaimed 
enforcement efforts against the shell which usually has no 
assets or is bankrupt prove futile the group said meanwhile 
the operator creates another shell company and repeats the rape 
and run process 
in 1985 a court order was obtained requiring the department to 
establish a computer system to contain data on the identity of 
owners of mining permits and to match them with violators of the 
act 
but rushforth said a series of congressional investigations 
showed the system was ineffective and accomplished none of its 
objectives 
harry snyder director of the surface mining office said he 
inherited a broken computer system that the government had spent 
millions of dollars on and which didnt work 
now he said youve got a new administration committed to 
enforce this law fairly and in a committed way 
</TEXT>
