<TEXT>
the soviet union is cooperating with dutch 
authorities in trying to locate and return a valuable collection of 
old master drawings that was sold illegally to the nazis and seized 
by russian troops during world war ii artnews magazine reported 
wednesday 
a copyrighted article in the magazines february issue which 
will appear on newsstands monday said that after years of balking 
at dutch diplomatic efforts to repatriate the drawings the soviets 
agreed to cooperate during a meeting with dutch cultural official 
jan riezenkamp in moscow last october 
the focus of the dutch governments search is a collection of 
491 old master drawings valued at 50 million to 75 million that 
once belonged to franz koenigs a germanborn dutch industrialist 
who assembled the art works in the 1920s 
the collection included works by correggio rembrandt titian 
anthony van dyck albrecht durer jeanhonore fragonard hans 
holbein filippino lippi peter paul rubens jacopo tintoretto and 
antoine watteau 
dutch concern over recovering the missing drawings from the 
soviet union was heightened when two of the drawings surfaced 
recently in new york and london in the hands of private dealers and 
collectors the magazine said their reappearance prompted the 
dutch government to file lawsuits for the drawings return 
artnews said a large portion of the koenigs collection was sold 
illegally to adolf hitlers agent hans posse in rotterdam during 
world war ii for an art museum that hitler planned to build in his 
native austria posse often bought art at forced sales from 
unwilling sellers paying far below market value the magazine said 
the koenigs drawings were moved to dresden germany which came 
under soviet occupation after the war the drawings and millions 
of other art treasures were transferred to the soviet union where 
the drawings disappeared and were feared destroyed 
the magazine said soviet and east german authorities repeatedly 
rebuffed dutch efforts to locate and repatriate the drawings during 
the 1940s and 1950s it quoted riezenkamp as crediting soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachevs liberal policies for the recent 
change in soviet attitude toward the dutch requests 
riezenkamp now believes at least some of the drawings eventually 
will be repatriated with soviet cooperation said the magazine 
which is published in new york 
</TEXT>
