<TEXT>
the white house worried about exposing 
reporters to danger during next months drug summit in colombia 
may put most of the press corps covering president bush in another 
country such as panama costa rica or venezuela spokesman marlin 
fitzwater said wednesday 
he said there was a good chance the press would be located 
somewhere other than colombia when bush visits there feb 15 for 
several hours of talks with president virgilio barco and officials 
of peru and bolivia 
other countries under consideration for the press include 
jamaica puerto rico and aruba 
the alternatesite plan would run counter to a longstanding 
policy of having the press corps close to bush on foreign trips 
there have been numerous reports of threatened violence against 
bush and others in colombia by cocaine drug lords angry about a 
government crackdown against their operations 
most recently cbs news said drug terrorists were buying 
surfacetoair missiles to try to shoot down bushs plane 
fitzwater said the secret service was confident it could provide 
protection for bush in colombia but that it has no authority to do 
the same for reporters 
tentative plans had called for the white house to set up filing 
facilities for the press at a commercial airport at cartagena near 
the expected summit site 
fitzwater said there was a lot of deep concern about having it 
at the airport since it was exposed to the general population 
the way to answer that concern he said is to put it 
someplace else 
traditionally 11 reporters accompany bush on air force one as a 
pool while the remainder of the press travel on a plane 
chartered by the white house and paid for by their companies 
the pool frequently is expanded to permit more photographers 
cameramen and reporters into situations where coverage is limited 
fitzwater said that under the plan being considered a pool of 
undetermined size would accompany bush to the actual summit while 
the overwhelming majority of the press would go elsewhere 
he said he had talked with a number of reporters about the idea 
and that they were generally favorable to having the filing 
center in another country 
fitzwater said that anybody who doesnt like it is free to go 
to cartagena on their own however it was unclear how anyone 
who traveled independently could get access to bush and the summit 
proceedings 
the press secretary said he was examining logistics about an 
alternate site such as how the press would be briefed on summit 
developments and the possibility that bush might go to the filing 
center afterward for a news conference 
the one thing im worried about are those sam surfacetoair 
