<TEXT>
the head of the federal communications 
commission told congress on wednesday he wants more stringent rules 
against drug involvement by broadcasters 
the commission chairman alfred sikes wrote rep john dingell 
dmich chairman of the energy and commerce committee that he had 
asked the commission staff for a thorough examination of the 
commissions 1986 character policy statement 
the current policy which was adopted under fcc chairman mark s 
fowler does not say whether such things as drug possession and 
pending drug charges against broadcasters should be taken into 
account during license proceedings 
until the 1986 fcc ruling any felony conviction automatically 
had been considered relevant to an applicants suitability to hold 
a broadcast license but the commission narrowed the scope of 
issues it was willing to consider 
there is no scarcity of lawabiding citizens interested in 
being broadcast licensees sikes wrote dingell today there 
are also fewer objective requirements associated with holding a 
broadcast license consequently in my view current or prospective 
broadcast licensees should be held to a higher standard than is 
reflected in the current policy statement 
dingell whose committee oversees the commission said sikes 
position is a refreshing change 
his commitment to thoroughly reexamining that policy goes a 
long way toward restoring my confidence in the fccs judgment and 
willingness to regulate in the public interest said dingell who 
battled continually with sikes deregulationminded predecessors 
fowler and dennis r patrick 
sikes last september announced the commission automatically 
would consider drug dealing convictions as possible grounds for 
yanking a broadcasters license but he did not mention drug 
possession convictions 
congress when it passed the 1988 antidrug abuse act denied 
federal benefits to drug violators but it did not say whether 
an fcc license was a federal benefit 
sikes wrote that although the commission had some discretion in 
drug matters involving broadcasters drug possession is not 
specifically mentioned as within the scope of the character policy 
statement 
misdemeanor drug convictions that do not deny federal benefits 
under the 1988 drug law also are not mentioned in the policy 
statement sikes said therefore such a conviction would not be 
considered relevant to an applicants basic qualifications in a 
license renewal or transfer proceeding sikes said 
the policy statement also does not mention drugassociated 
activities such as money laundering extortion theft burglary or 
robbery it says specifically that homicide will not disqualify an 
applicant 
but sikes said the commission retains the discretion to 
consider misconduct that is so egregious as to shock the 
conscience 
in felony cases sikes added an applicant may buy or sell a 
station until the charges are proven the commission could 
however grant approval of a license contingent upon the outcome of 
the pending criminal proceeding 
applicants convicted of misconduct at one station may not 
automatically be disqualified from owning other stations sikes 
said 
the commissions drug policy was called into question when in 
1988 it renewed the license of williamsburg county broadcasting 
corp to operate wkspam in kingstree sc after the companys 
principal owner gregory knop was convicted of a cocaine charge 
in its september revisions the commission said knops 
conviction raised questions about williamsburgs qualifications to 
hold the license 
