<TEXT>
latin american countries will have to rely 
less on foreign borrowing as they try to rebuild their economies 
from the debt crisis of the 1980s world bank president barber 
conable said wednesday 
except possibly in eastern europe no group of nations is 
facing such a daunting task of reform and reconstruction as latin 
america conable said in a speech at the colegio de mexico a 
graduate school and thinktank 
to recover countries will have to shrink the size of government 
bureaucracies that expanded from the fifties through last decade 
into financing industry infrastructure social services and 
security as well as increasing their foreign borrowings conable 
said 
we have learned from the experience of developing countries 
and socialist countries of eastern europe that excessively 
centralized economic management leads to such inefficiencies that 
ultimately economic development comes to a halt he said 
in brazil today he said salaries of public employees and 
interest on the domestic debt take up 90 percent of public sector 
revenue leaving little for investment or public services 
the world bank will continue to participate in latin american 
development he said but countries should look to direct foreign 
private investment to replace some of the public borrowing 
the channels for the flow of commercial capital to developing 
countries have been damaged by the debt crisis he said 
external capital will no longer flow in quantities and with the 
ease with which it was available in the 70s and even if it did 
developing countries should not borrow as they did in the 70s 
three latin countries head the list of developing countries that 
owe foreign debtors the most brazil then mexico and argentina 
he said latin america and africa had been most severely hit by 
the crisis 
more developing countries have suffered reverses in the past 
decade than have experienced success 
conable called mexicos economic reform program one of the 
most ambitious courageous and determined recently undertaken by 
any country and said it could serve as an example for other latin 
