floridas black widow got a 
permanent stay from the state supreme court wednesday less than 20 
hours before she was to die in the electric chair 
the reprieve given to judi buenoano condemned for the fatal 
poisoning of her husband 19 years ago is good for the rest of her 
death warrant the court said it will schedule briefs and arguments 
later this week 
only one woman has been executed in the united states since the 
us supreme court reinstated the death penalty 13 years ago in 
1984 velma barfield died by injection in north carolina for 
poisoning her boyfriend 
ms buenoano nicknamed the black widow by prosecutors was 
under her first death warrant none of the 21 men electrocuted in 
florida since the state reinstated capital punishment have died 
under a first warrant 
it is up to gov bob martinez to decide whether a second warrant 
is signed but he is not expected to act until the state supreme 
court decides whether to grant ms buenoano a second trial 
attorneys for ms buenoano filed a notice of appeal with the 
high court wednesday morning after the orlando judge who sentenced 
her to death in 1985 refused to stay the execution late tuesday 
ms buenoano 46 was sentenced to death for the murder of her 
husband air force sgt james e goodyear soon after he returned 
from service in vietnam 
goodyears body was exhumed more than a decade after his death 
when officials began investigating a car bombing in pensacola ms 
buenoano was convicted of that 1983 bombing in which she was 
accused of trying to kill boyfriend john gentry after he stopped 
taking poisonfilled vitamin capsules 
the levels of arsenic examiners found in goodyears body 
indicated he had suffered chronic exposure to the poison ms 
buenoano changed her name to a spanish approximation of goodyear 
after her husbands death 
ms buenoano was also found guilty of killing her 19yearold 
paralyzed son michael goodyear by pushing him overboard during a 
1980 canoe trip 
ms buenoano received life sentences for both of those crimes 
she is suspected but has not been charged of using arsenic to 
kill a commonlaw husband in trinidad colo in 1977 
in each case ms buenoano collected or stood to collect 
thousands of dollars in life insurance benefits 
ms buenoano was transferred from her death row cell in broward 
correctional institution west of fort lauderdale to a special 
death watch cell in florida state prison monday spokesman bob 
macmaster said tuesday 
