parliaments foreign affairs committee 
approved a bill wednesday calling for a sixmonth extension on the 
may deadline for the united states to dismantle its military 
installations in greece 
under the terms of a defense accord that expired in december 
1988 the united states has until may 21 to remove personnel 
property and materiel from four major bases and several smaller 
installations unless a new agreement is reached 
the proposed new deadline for dismantling the bases is nov 21 
the full parliament will debate the bill on monday state et1 
television said 
representatives of the conservative and socialist parties on the 
standing committee for foreign affairs and defense voted in favor 
of the extension requested by the united states so negotiations on 
a new defense pact could continue 
the communistled coalition of the left and progress the third 
party supporting premier xenophon zolotas administration voted 
against the bill it was passed by a simple majority in the 
50member committee 
the conservatives and socialists hold 276 seats in the 
300member parliament the communists are opposed to the bases but 
have said they would not withdraw from the government if a law is 
passed postponing the bases removal 
the zolotas administration was appointed after inconclusive 
general elections in november 
new elections are slated for april leaving the next government 
to determine the fate of the bases with the united states 
a previous fiveyear defense and economic cooperation accord 
negotiated by the former socialist government and washington 
expired in december 1988 it gave the united states 17 months to 
dismantle the bases if no new accord was reached 
the bases were established in greece in the mid1950s 
after 17 rounds of fruitless negotiations athens and washington 
suspended talks before national elections last june a shortlived 
coalition formed by the conservative and communist parties after 
those elections put the issue on hold 
the socialist government headed by former premier andreas 
papandreou had demanded any new defense accord include guarantees 
of aid in case of aggression by nato ally turkey which the united 
states has been wary of providing 
greece and turkey nearly went to war in march 1987 over disputed 
territorial waters in the aegean sea 
