<TEXT>
the food and drug administration threatened 
legal action wednesday against an american heart association food 
labeling program it said could mislead consumers but the heart 
association decided to go ahead with the the program 
the fda said in a letter that the food labeling program could be 
risking regulatory action it said there is a very real 
possibility that the fda would find one or more foods under your 
program to be misbranded meaning they might carry misleading 
labels 
the program known as heartguide is an ambitious effort by the 
heart association to make consumers smarter shoppers by identifying 
products low in saturated fat total fat cholesterol and sodium 
products tested and approved by the association for a fee 
would carry a symbol made up of a red heart and a check mark 
the fda has authority to act only after products go on sale it 
can then require that companies change labels the agency can also 
block the sale of improperly labeled items or seize them said jeff 
nesbit an fda spokesman 
vicki anderson a spokeswoman for heartguide said the program 
scheduled to begin officially monday has been under development 
for three years it has been discussed with the fda throughout the 
past year she said 
we were expecting a letter from the fda but we did not 
anticipate this she said heartguide officials thought the fda 
would take a neutral stance on the program not one where they 
would exercise their regulatory jurisdiction 
the heart association however is proceeding with its launch of 
the program monday weve already talked to the companies 
participating in the program and they are in said another 
heartguide spokeswoman jamy poth 
more than 100 brands of margarine oil crackers and vegetables 
already have been tested and approved they include mazola corn 
oil promise margarine pam cooking sprays melba toast and hanover 
frozen vegetables 
however the next phase of the program in which cereals 
cheese cookies pasta salad dressings and other foods will be 
included has been put on hold while the heart association 
negotiates further with the fda anderson said 
none of the labeled products in the first phase is currently 
available on the shelves anderson said manufacturers had begun 
printing containers with the labels but that products were not yet 
ready for shipment to supermarkets 
we all knew that something was coming from the fda said 
john cady president of the national food processors association 
which has vigorously opposed the program 
what we see here is a realization by the government agencies 
that you have a nonprofit private organization a nonregulated 
organization trying to establish a set of rules and regulations on 
labeling for a fee i think thats wrong 
the makers of mazola products said they had not yet decided how 
to react to the fdas action said gail griffin spokeswoman for 
cpc international of englewood cliffs nj that is the parent 
company of best foods which makes mazola 
the fdas letter was addressed to heart association president 
dr myron l weisfeldt of johns hopkins university in baltimore 
acting commissioner james s benson wrote that the heartguide 
program could increase consumer confusion and hamper any 
comprehensive solution to the food labeling problem 
he invited the heart association instead to join with the fda 
and other groups in our current initiative to develop a 
comprehensive revision of the food label to promote good nutrition 
 
weisfeldt said in a statement on behalf of the 27 million 
aha volunteers across the united states i want to say we are 
deeply disappointed by mr bensons letter particularly since it 
has come just a few days before our program was to begin but he 
said i would like to emphasize that we are not closing down the 
heartguide program 
the program has been controversial from its inception the 
national food processors association has opposed the program on the 
grounds that it charges a hefty fee up to 640000 depending 
upon a products sales and that competitive pressures make it 
difficult for eligible companies to refuse to join 
it also opens the door to similar programs by other groups who 
want to charge money to food processors for getting their 
endorsement said ellen morton a spokeswoman 
the program has also been criticized on the grounds that it 
promotes certain foods instead of promoting the idea of a healthy 
overall diet 
the heart association said its educational program will make 
clear that heartguideapproved foods should be incorporated into a 
diet that is beneficial overall 
</TEXT>
