an industry spokesman said wednesday that 
president bush has decided to suspend belowcost timber sales from 
10 national forests in the fiscal year that will begin oct 1 
barry polsky of the american forest resource alliance which 
includes timber companies sawmills and other enterprises said the 
shutdown will be announced in bushs budget proposals sent to 
congress next week 
a spokewoman for agriculture secretary clayton yeutter who was 
out of town referred the question to agriculture department budget 
director stephen b dewhurst who declined comment 
polsky said the 10 forests in fiscal 1988 harvested 262 million 
board feet of timber and provided about 3000 jobs local 
communities received 598 million as their share of federal 
revenue from the timber sales 
polsky in a telephone interview said that preservationists 
want to stop timber sales of all kinds and have been partially 
successful in limited areas where protected species of animals 
exist 
in some forests they cant find a species to protect so 
theyve gone after forests that sell timber below costs he said 
admittedly polsky added some forests do sell cutrate timber 
but theres no federal rule against that and national forests on 
the average do make money for taxpayers 
but belowcost timber sales are losing practices in specific 
forests so there has been pressure to end the practice he said 
polsky identified 10 national forests which tentatively have 
been earmarked for terminated timber sales 
montana beaverhead 
