president bush is preparing to propose an aid 
program for panama totaling more than 1 billion to help the 
country recover from recent warfare and long years of corrupt 
military rule us officials said wednesday night 
congressional leaders were briefed on the program wednesday and 
a formal announcement is expected thursday said one official 
asking not to be identified 
a second senior official confirming the amount on condition of 
anonymity cautioned not all of it is new money 
about half the program will be in cash and the remainder in 
credits the first official said 
aside from development aid the program will include loan 
guarantees and programs to encourage investment he said 
the administration hopes that other countries experienced in 
foreign aid including japan and western european countries will 
follow the us lead and make contributions of their own 
damage estimates from the dec 20 us invasion vary widely 
ranging from a few hundred million dollars to 2 billion or more 
the united states already has released 400 million in panamanian 
assets frozen in the united states in earlier efforts to topple the 
regime led by gen manuel antonio noriega ousted in the invasion 
according to the official the proposal will will require a 
supplemental appropriation by the congress for a portion of the 
money but a sizeable percentage will be paid for in cuts from aid 
programs to other countries 
a big chunk will be out of the taxpayers pockets the 
official said predicting a tough fight in finding the money 
he said panama although a small country of about 2 million 
people requires substantial aid because successive military 
governments including noriegas stole a good portion of the 
national treasury 
the 1 billion if approved would make panama one the largest 
recipients of us aid per capita after two years of economic 
sanctions that dealt heavy blows to the economy 
the official disclosed details after president bush told his 
news conference he was determined to try to help repair the 
wounds repair the damage 
i mourn the loss of innocent civilians in panama or anywhere 
else bush said 
bush sidestepped the question of compensation for civilian 
deaths saying he was not sure of all details of the planned aid 
package 
officials have said there was not much sentiment to include 
compensation for the families of the more than 200 civilians 
killed the pentagon estimated 220 civilian deaths possibly 
including some soldiers out of uniform 
panamanian officials have put the toll at 202 while some church 
groups have put the numbers as high as 1000 
asked what he would say to the panamanian survivors bush said 
he would tell them look you lost some panamanian lives 
innocent life was lost and yet 92 percent of the people in panama 
strongly supported the action of the united states isnt that 
significant 
a white house official earlier characterized the aid package as 
very broad covering housing trade and debt panama is in 
arrears on its obligations to international lending institutions 
and its total foreign debt amounts to a heavy 534 million 
the assistance package bush aides are preparing will include 
help for rebuilding homes that were damaged in the dec 20 
invasion and some kind of multilateral effort to help panama 
with its debt said another official spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
earlier this week the white house announced that the overseas 
private investment corp the federal agency that promotes us 
investment abroad will recruit us businesses to undertake 
investment in panama opic will sponsor a tour of panama for 
business leaders in late february 
the white house has said there is no money earmarked for panama 
in the 1991 budget that bush will send to congress on monday any 
supplemental appropriation would apply in the current fiscal year 
vice president dan quayle could take the specifics of the plan 
when he travels to panama this weekend for talks with the new 
government the white house official said 
were going to be discussing their requirements and our 
resources said quayles press secretary david beckwith 
quayle is traveling to panama after attending saturdays 
presidential inauguration in honduras his mission is to urge 
recognition by other governments for the usinstalled panamanian 
government and to try to soothe the anger among latin nations 
caused by the invasion 
