fellow at the center at georgetown university expressed doubts 
that bishops could meet the may 31 deadline set by the vatican for 
their reactions to the 434page draft 
the bishops need a lot more time to examine such an important 
document and to consult with theologians about it in formulating 
their comments he said in an interview 
this is the the most important document to come out since 
vatican ii he said it will set the parameters of how the 
catholic faith is taught in the 21st century 
a bishops committee headed by archbishop oscar lipscomb of 
mobile ala was set up early this month for a preliminary study 
but the bishops dont hold a business meeting until next november 
reese 45 whose 1989 book archbishop describes policies 
and views of the churchs us archbishops has another scheduled 
for publication this fall also by harper amp row on scholarly 
reactions to the proposed catechism 
the long often complex and technically worded document was 
produced by a special bishops commission headed by cardinal 
joseph ratzinger chief of the vaticans doctrinal office 
marked sub secreto under secrecy it was distributed in 
december to the worlds 2500 bishops it first was proposed at a 
world synod of bishops in 1985 by cardinal bernard law of boston 
provisionally entitled catechism for the universal church 
its structure follows a longtime pattern much like the last such 
universal roman catechism issued in 1566 after the council of 
trent 
there are three main sections one on the apostles creed 
another on the churchs seven sacraments and the other on the ten 
commandments followed by an epilogue on prayer 
this treatment in separate compartments make it difficult to 
show the relationships of faith and life reese said the 
structure itself automatically sets up dichotomies between the 
world and faith rather than their being integrated 
he noted that the vatican council emphasizes christianity as 
working in the world rather than withdrawal from it 
he said that the scholarly appraisals say the document reflects 
a separation between the spiritual and the natural the religious 
and the secular vatican ii sought to overcome that dichotomy 
the document frequently uses the word man and men in 
references that apply to all people male and female for example 
some headings read man in search for god god meets man 
the dignity of man 
the sexually exclusivist language is terrible reese said 
this day and age must be much more sensitive 
while the document frequently quotes the bible reese said the 
use of scripture is very poor usually quoted in prooftext 
fashion to defend various doctrines 
it doesnt give the kind of comprehensive treatment that takes 
into consideration the historical context and literary forms he 
said treatment of scripture is very very prevatican ii 
he said the document recognizes ecumenical efforts for church 
unity particularly with the eastern orthodox but certainly 
needs strengthening in references to protestants 
some of the language is confusing and needs to be clarified 
he said it needs to be improved to stress the unity catholics 
have with protestants in baptism and in scriptures 
however he said the document also had positive elements such 
as pointing up obligations for peace justice and preservation of 
the environment and also in dealing with judaism 
the document like vatican ii says jews should not be blamed 
for christs crucifixion 
unlike the old council of trent catechism the new draft 
addresses issues unheard of then such as nuclear and chemical 
warfare surrogate motherhood biogenetic research toxic waste and 
reckless driving 
</TEXT>
