causerelated investing once was considered a 
cockamamie idea concocted by liberal crackpots to make money on 
companies that renounce ties to south africa shun defense 
contracts and dont pollute 
over the past two decades however it has snowballed into a 
multibillion dollar chunk of the investment business and has 
branched into other areas ranging from credit cards to a 
longdistance telephone service 
just the amount of money funneled into what are called socially 
responsible mutual funds has grown so much that the wall street 
establishment hungry for business in a depressed industry has 
started to woo potential clients by touting moneymaking 
opportunities tied to social and environmental concerns 
some staid brokerages for example now offer what they call 
screened investments for clients who dont want to own securities 
in companies that do business with south africas white minority 
government others have established funds investing in companies 
that recycle or make only peacetime products 
i think the traditional people are feeling a little funny 
they laughed they made fun and for 20 years they said this would 
be a flash in the pan said rosalyn will a project director at 
the council on economic priorities a new york group that 
researches social investing i dont think its going to be that 
way 
over the past several years the amount of money channeled into 
socially responsible investment funds has multiplied to more than 
45 billion said the social investment forum a bostonbased 
association that promotes the concept of social investing 
many of these funds have been quite profitable despite 
predictions by some finance professionals that using social 
criteria for screening investments is silly and risky 
it totally deflated that argument said gordon davidson 
executive director of the social investment forum theyre now 
beginning to set up their own social investment funds 
two of the topranked mutual funds in 1989 ranked by lipper 
analytical securities were social funds the parnassus fund earned 
a 4244 percent return and ariel growth fund earned 3997 percent 
one of the pioneers in social funds the pax world fund inc 
formed during the antivietnam war movement in 1970 also ranked 
among the best by lipper last year earning a 2492 percent return 
pax world president luther tyson attributed part of the funds 
success to strict criteria for what types of investments it will 
buy 
we are the only fund that defines so carefully how we dont 
invest in warrelated goods and services tyson said we work 
out a definition that can be monitored 
for example he said pax world wont invest in the 600 largest 
defense department contractors using the pentagons own lists as a 
guide the fund also asks companies to respond to a questionnaire 
about their environmental record before deciding whether to include 
them in its securities portfolio 
most social investment funds stick to basic securities stocks 
governmentbacked bonds or certificates of deposit none are known 
