<TEXT>
take a longrange perspective on america as 
most highly successful investors do and you might develop not just 
a less frantic view of the future but a fatter wallet too 
it will relieve you of worrying over the difficulties of savings 
and loan bailouts the intractable federal deficit the chances of 
recession and the possibilities of a tax cut or a tax increase 
many of the economic worries that concern people at any 
particular time disappear from the scene to be replaced by other 
concerns many of the tax financial and economic maneuvers of 
government offset each other 
you might even argue that discussions of tax increases or 
decreases should barely concern you even though every financial 
adviser in the country will warn you that tax strategies are 
necessary for your financial existence 
the evidence about taxes however is that they seldom really 
shift or that if they do it is for only a very limited time 
taxes were cut sharply in the early 1980s by the end of the decade 
all were offset by increases 
in fact economist h eric heinemann points out that individual 
income taxes last year consumed about 10 percent of personal 
income or about the same as the average of the 45 years since 
world war ii 
this isnt to say that congress shouldnt be watched only that 
watching income tax maneuvers might be to watch the wrong things 
while income tax increases and decreases offset each other social 
security taxes do not 
heinemann points out that since 1985 social security taxes 
averaged 94 percent of personal income up from 29 percent from 
1950 through 1955 while in both periods individual income taxes 
averaged 102 percent 
it may also be unwise to get upset about economic numbers such 
as monthly retail sales unemployment inflation rates and the 
like since increases or decreases in any of these can be revised 
out of existence 30 days later 
the longrange view also permits you to see the economy as the 
cyclical creature that it is and understand that what is down 
today might be up five years from now securities real estate 
interest rates inflation rates 
the economy seldom stays the same instead it rises and falls 
expands and contracts a full cycle often occurring in less than 
five years but even those who know this get caught up in the 
interim excitement 
that excitement accounts for such things as people flocking to 
buy stocks at the top of the market spurred on by tales of higher 
prices to come and real estate developers rushing to build as a 
glut approaches 
at the other extreme are people abandoning the midwest rustbelt 
as it was strengthening into what is now one of the stronger 
economic areas and abandoning real estate in houston when prices 
could only go up as they have 
while the nature of economies is to grow and shrink rather than 
remain the same there is in the united states a very clear 
constant the expansions are larger than the contractions 
proof of this can be found in a comparison of america in 1915 
and 1985 in the intervening time there occurred two highly 
disruptive wars and several lesser ones a destructive depression 
and bouts with runaway inflation 
the following figures come from a joint study by the us bureau 
of the census and the conference board 
in 1915 infant mortality per 1000 births was 99 in 1985 it 
was 11 life expectancy at age 20 was 65 years in the earlier 
period and 76 years in the later one 
homeownership as a percentage of all married couples rose from 
46 percent to 776 percent gross national product measured by the 
same dollar 1985 in each instance rose to 3998 trillion from 
468 billion 
gnp per capita jumped to 16777 from 4660 an index of 
productivity to 490 from 100 average hourly wages of workers in 
manufacturing from 244 to 953 
but in between those years there were many bad times and many 
frantic moments for those who couldnt lift their heads high enough 
to see the bigger picture 
