<TEXT>
middleclass drug addiction was good business 
for american hospitals until too many of them figured that out 
clinics hospitals and healthcare companies that jumped to 
capitalize on the highprofit field of residential drug and alcohol 
treatment now frequently find themselves with empty beds while 
public programs for those unable to pay struggle to keep pace with 
demand 
addicts in some parts of the country wait six months or more to 
get into a publicly financed program but about 40 percent of the 
beds in private treatment centers lie empty experts say 
if you can pay you can get treatment if you cannot pay 
youre going to be put on a waiting list in most places said 
bill butynski executive director of the national association of 
state alcohol and drug abuse directors 
this disparity is growing the experts say despite an increase 
in public funds for substanceabuse treatment over the last decade 
and a growing awareness among employers and society in general of 
the need for treatment 
the need for treatment is higher than it has ever been but 
the demand is a little different said mike ford president of 
the national association of addiction treatment providers which 
represents private treatment centers 
treatment options are being dictated increasingly by economics 
as the government employers and insurers try to rein in the 
soaring costs of health care he and many other experts say 
the economic tail is wagging the clinical dog said norman 
hoffmann a clinical psychologist at the ramsey clinic in st paul 
minn and director of the clinics chemical addiction treatment 
outcome registry 
the result is intense scrutiny over the need for residential or 
inpatient treatment which can run upwards of 15000 and an 
increasing reliance on less expensive outpatient programs 
hospitals rushed into the extendedcare livein treatment 
business but many now find they cannot fill their spaces studies 
have shown residential and outpatient treatment to be about 
equally effective and insurance companies have seized on this in 
arguing that more addicts should be channeled into the less 
expensive programs 
but treatment providers say residential treatment typically 
about 28 days is more appropriate for some addicts especially 
those who need to be physically separated from their everyday 
environment to break their dependency 
private residential treatment programs began popping up in the 
mid1970s after medicare began covering livein treatment private 
insurance companies also began including coverage in their packages 
by the early 1980s residential coverage was common practice 
the number of freestanding treatment facilities was growing and 
more hospitals were setting aside beds for drug and alcohol 
treatment 
but in 1983 medicare which often drives medical practices in 
this country because of its huge budget now more than 100 billion 
implemented a program designed to cut hospital costs under this 
program medicare agreed to pay hospitals a specified amount for 
treatment of various disorders and illnesses categorized in 
diagnostic related groups or drgs 
before drgs a hospital could be reimbursed at the same rate for 
all inpatient care whether it applied to a cancer patient 
requiring intense medical supervision or an alcoholic in for 
detoxification and needing less attention 
but under drgs hospitals can no longer get top dollar for 
addiction treatment beds some have begun converting those beds to 
more profitable uses including units for organ transplant and 
cancer patients which need the higher levels of medical staffing 
hospitals provide said ken estes spokesman for the national 
association of addiction treatment providers 
employers and insurers meanwhile are feeling the effects of 
skyrocketing healthcare costs some rising more than 15 percent a 
year 
they began their own efforts to cut back usually by reducing 
coverage and scrutinizing use of benefits now companies and 
insurance companies increasingly are turning to managed care 
in which an outside company reviews claims to determine whether 
treatment was medically necessary 
this leads to decisions on a level of care based not on what a 
patient needs but on economic considerations said ford 
as a result he said private treatment programs have found it 
more difficult to get patients to fill their beds because more 
employers and insurance companies are steering away from 
residential treatment 
though outpatient programs are usually less expensive 
participants sometimes wind up paying more outofpocket for them 
because insurance coverage is generally not as good as for 
inpatient programs 
the treatment industry is struggling to match up with what the 
buyers of services want to pay for and in a nutshell they want it 
very cheap said w james nicol president of comprehensive care 
corp one of the largest providers of residential treatment 
services 
nicol blames many of compcares recent financial troubles it 
reported a 47 million loss for the third quarter of 1989 and 
occupancy rates that have fallen to 46 percent on government and 
business efforts to cut healthcare costs 
his company and others like it are responding to the financial 
austerity by shifting some of their emphasis to outpatient 
programs although historically these have never been as 
profitable he said 
since fiscal 1982 federal block grants to states for alcohol 
drug and mental health services have risen from 429 million to 
765 million in fiscal 1989 this year the total is expected to 
reach 12 billion 
more than 3 billion in federal state and local funds were 
spent on alcohol and drug abuse treatment in 1987 according to 
government data 
in fiscal 1988 the national association of state alcohol and 
drug abuse directors counted 6926 substanceabuse programs that 
received public money a 50 percent increase from fiscal 1984 
federal government data counted 984 private forprofit centers 
in 1987 these data based on a voluntary survey also showed 4503 
private nonprofit programs that year some of which may receive 
public funds and may also be counted in the state directors 
numbers 
few programs are financed and operated solely by the government 
most of the time states use their federal and state dollars to 
contract with private nonprofit centers for treatment services 
these funds also usually require the programs to provide service to 
anyone who needs it regardless of ability to pay 
thats probably the biggest reason for the waiting lists 
said olive jacob an albany nybased consultant on alcohol and 
drug issues 
adding to the problem she said is that the federal government 
and many states prohibit their funds being used for private 
profitmaking programs 
she and others say the problem of waiting lists which is most 
severe in the larger east and west coast cities could be eased if 
the federal and state governments were more flexible in the use of 
their treatment dollars 
ford said that if the government set a price for a treatment 
service offered it to private providers and said take it or 
leave it theyd take it 
</TEXT>
