<TEXT>
paul a lara started using marijuana 
alcohol pcp and lsd when he was 14 years old in time he went to 
school only to see friends who could sell him more drugs 
it wasnt until he was 25 a veteran of a 30day hospital drug 
treatment regime and a sixmonth livein program that he was ready 
to get off the drugs and get on with his life 
but the county of los angeles wasnt ready for him 
lara with his insurance depleted years ago and little money 
left was put on a waiting list for the countyfinanced impact 
program an intensive six to ninemonth stay at a residential 
treatment center with 90 beds 
i had to call every day for three weeks before they told me i 
could come in for an interview said lara when i got here 
they said theyve got a space and its now or never i went into 
this place with the clothes on my back 
lara who was admitted in november was in some senses one of 
the lucky ones he managed to keep calling 
many of the 1500 to 1800 people on waiting lists for los 
angeles countys livein treatment centers disappear before anyone 
can help they sink deeper into their addictions sometimes getting 
arrested even killed because of their craving 
los angeles county four times the size of rhode island and home 
to 87 million people has just 650 treatment beds available 
through 18 publicly financed programs 
only two hospitals in the county offer publicly financed 
detoxification usually the first step in treatment in which an 
addicts body is flushed of drugs 
after detox people in need of livein treatment programs can be 
placed on waiting lists for as long as six months methadone 
clinics and outpatient programs have four to fivemonth waiting 
lists 
we cannot provide treatment on demand its as simple as 
that said irma strantz the countys drug program administrator 
the number of people waiting for treatment far exceeds by 
multiples of two or three the available spaces said maury 
weiner who heads the tarzana treatment center in the san fernando 
valley 
officials at public centers say the situation will only get 
worse they point to a drug problem that shows no signs of abating 
erratic state and federal financing and the difficulties of 
treating an increasing number of addicts who are pregnant or suffer 
aids 
there are people screaming for treatment and its 
heartbreaking that we are not able to provide the treatment for 
them said clyde w oden president and chief executive of the 
watts health foundation 
for somebody seeking public treatment persistence is key 
officials at joint efforts a san pedro outpatient program tell 
people on waiting lists to call twice a day to see if a bed is 
available for detoxification 
when beds open up its up to the addicts to get themselves to 
the hospital for the four to sevenday detox before coming back to 
joint efforts for counseling 
joint efforts executive director pat herrera duran said the 
wait is at least three weeks for detox in which time addicts often 
deplete family funds and rob and assault to sustain a drug habit 
whatever it is theyre doing to get their drugs theyll 
continue to do she said 
while public centers struggle privately operated treatment 
facilities have beds to spare at prices as high as 1000 a day 
for treatment only the rich or those with good insurance can 
afford it 
in pasadena a few miles from the impact center the summit 
share unit at st luke medical center has occupants for just 10 of 
its 20 beds for a monthlong program that costs about 11000 
summit sponsors drug and alcohol awareness seminars as part of its 
marketing campaign 
