<TEXT>
santa fe pacific corp plans to reduce employment 
on its railroad by 2700 jobs over five years officials of the 
company say 
the reductions would take place through job buyouts attrition 
and possible layoffs and would affect both union and whitecollar 
workers said robert gerht spokesman for chicagobased santa fe 
the cuts would likely affect santa fe railway across its 
11500mile system officials said 
there is no specific timetable for the cuts which would reduce 
employment with the railroad from the current 18000 to about 
15300 according to the company 
some buyouts will be voluntary and some wont gerht said 
this is part of an overall plan to make the railroad more 
efficient and competitive 
in a statement issued tuesday santa fe pacific corp parent 
company of the railroad said it lost 2094 million or 133 a 
share in the fourth quarter because of a charge taken to establish 
reserves for covering costs of the workforce reduction and other 
railway restructurings the pretax charge totaled 3896 million 
the quarterly loss compared with net income of 1561 million 
or 99 cents a share in the fourth quarter of 1988 reflecting a 
136 million gain on the sale of a portion of the companys 
pipeline operations 
the railway actually had an excellent quarter to finish out 
1989 said robert krebs chairman and president of santa fe 
pacific if not for the charge he said the railway would have 
reported a 40 percent increase in operating income 
santa fe railway reported fourthquarter operating income of 67 
million before the restructuring costs up from 477 million a 
year earlier 
for the year santa fe pacific reported net income of 146 
million or 9 cents a share compared with a net loss of 465 
million or 30 cents a share in 1988 
the santa fe railway has been steadily reducing employment for 
several years about three years ago it took 85 crew members to 
run a santa fe train from chicago to los angeles the railroad 
currently uses 40 crew members on the same run and company 
officials expect to cut that number to about 30 gehrt said 
company officials said that the proposed union job cuts are 
provided for in recently negotiated labor contracts with some units 
of the united transportation union and the brotherhood of 
locomotive engineers the railroad is negotiating to reach similar 
agreements with other bargaining units officials said 
