a top regulator told congress today that 
president bushs 50 billion bailout of the savings and loan 
industry is probably too low 
l william seidman chairman of the federal deposit insurance 
corp and chairman of the new bailout agency the resolution trust 
corp said the money provided in legislation last august would be 
adequate only if the government seized no more than an additional 
40 billion worth of sampls 
as of jan 16 the rtc had seized 333 institutions with assets 
totaling 136 billion the loss on those is about 42 billion he 
said 
however the treasury departments office of thrift supervision 
is predicting that another 225 to 295 institutions with assets of 
160 billion to 200 billion will fail 
we have found no reason to question the reasonableness of 
those estimates seidman told the house banking committee 
the likely size of the loss 50 billion as provided by the 
sampl bill is probably too low a figure he said 
however he added it is very difficult to provide a more 
definitive number and said under any scenario the 50 billion 
should as far as losses are concerned carry the rtc into 
1991 
seidman went a step beyond testimony on tuesday from deputy 
treasury secretary john e robson who said i cant tell you 
with certainty that the 50 billion is going to be enough 
on tuesday robson said the thrift office was compiling a new 
