<DOCNO> AP900124-0262 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the owner of a denver printing company surrenders the keys of 
his twobedroom condominum to a lender because the units net value 
is far less than the balance of a second mortgage 
a government employee in florida worries he wont have enough 
money after lowering the selling price on his house to repay a 
homeequity loan plus put a down payment on new property 
the slumped housing market not only is erasing homeseller 
profits its beginning to put a damper on the 111 billion 
industry for homeequity loans and lines of credit which only a 
few years ago ballooned into one of the nations most popular forms 
of borrowing 
peddled by bankers eager to lend money these loans have been 
used by homeowners to finance everything from vacations to college 
for the kids backed by the properties themselves as collateral 
they are especially popular because the interest generally is 
deductible under the 1986 tax reform which is phasing out the 
deductibility of other consumer loans the rates also are much 
lower compared with personal loans 
borrowing against the house remains a convenient way to tap into 
one of the nations greatest pools of wealth an estimated 45 
trillion in homeowner equity but eroding housing prices in many 
parts of the country have reduced some of that equity limiting 
homeowners borrowing power and leaving some past borrowers with 
more loan than equity experts say 
as a result some banks thrifts and other lenders have 
tightened their credit policies and at least one expert predicts a 
significant number may start to flee the homeequity business this 
year 
i think more people will be looking at their homes as shelter 
than as an investment said a gary shilling head a new york 
economics firm that bears his name they thought they had this 
neverending appreciating asset that they could tap but its not 
ken k a denver printer who preferred not to reveal his last 
name for publication found that out the hard way 
he said he recently returned to a lender the twobedroom condo 
bought as an investment five years ago after the balance on a 
second loan came due since the condos market value had fallen to 
around 30000 from the 52500 purchase price he realized that 
even by selling the condo he couldnt come up with the 9000 
needed to repay the lender 
the situation isnt quite as grim for a florida government 
official who also wished to remain anonymous however he is 
concerned that by consistently lowering the 200000 asking price 
of his home therell be little left to put a deposit on another 
house and repay a 25000 homeequity credit line 
despite these types of problems many financial institutions 
remain optimistic about homeequity loans noting that defaults 
remain relatively rare and prudent credit policies should forestall 
serious defaults 
the american bankers association said that in 1988 the last 
year for which complete data was available losses from home equity 
loan defaults among all commercial banks totaled 220 million 
thats considered negligible compared with the billions in 
potentially bad third world loans for example 
some delinquency rates however have risen at the end of the 
third quarter of last year 093 percent of all openend credit 
lines were delinquent or at least 30 days past due up from 086 
percent the same time in 1988 aba figures show the delinquency 
rate on closedend loans was 169 percent in the third quarter 
down from 176 percent it said 
an open or revolving line of credit lets borrowers set aside 
an amount of money to be used when needed a closedend loan or 
second mortgage provides a fixed dollar amount 
a softer realestate market coupled with a rise in delinquency 
rates has prompted many lenders to emphasize borrowers ability to 
repay rather than a homes appraised value 
a home equity loan is more a personal loan than a real estate 
loan said paul fritts director of the division of supervision 
at the federal deposit insurance corp unless you have good solid 
equity together with a good work record i think it will be more 
difficult to get those loans 
fritts said some banks that may have taken a chance on 
homeowners who were considered riskier than average when housing 
values rose are rejecting their loan applications now 
a few bankers said privately that theyve started restricting 
home equity credit lines and loans mainly to homeowners on which 
they hold the primary mortgage or to longstanding customers with 
reputable credit histories 
banks also are less likely to lend beyond their standard credit 
limits which typically run to about 80 percent of the available 
equity in a home fritts said when housing values were firmer a 
few banks extended credit to as much as 90 percent he said 
at connecticut national bank in hartford the maximum credit 
limit was trimmed several weeks ago partly because we saw that 
the new england real estate market was starting to soften said 
donald grigley whos in charge of the banks installment finance 
businesses he said that although losses from defaults remain low 
the bank had noticed a slight increase in late payments 
frequent late payments will prompt lenders to review a loan 
contract and borrowers credit record and in some cases to order 
a reappraisal of the property used as collateral 
however as long as borrowers pay on time they have little to 
worry about even if the balance exceeds the equity in their home 
because of declining real estate prices experts say 
still paul havemann a vice president at butler njbased hsh 
associates which publishes mortgage market information predicts 
the housing slump will help prompt some lenders to stop offering 
homeequity credit altogether this year 
havemann said he already has seen some signs of a pullout its 
harder to find lenders in the home equity business for his monthly 
survey of rates 
</TEXT>
