<TEXT>
interior secretary manual lujan in a bid to 
end a decadeold battle with environmental groups agreed today to 
create a new computer system to make it easier for the government 
to suspend coal mining permits issued to past violators of the 1977 
strip mining law 
interior department officials said the agreement signals a new 
and more cooperative approach to the concerns of environmentalists 
on the part of president bush and his administration 
in the exchange for the dropping of a law suit lujan agreed to 
a detailed work plan to improve the computerized applicant 
violator system maintained by the departments office of surface 
mining 
the system has been widely regarded as a failure 
our aim is fair evenhanded enforcement of the surface mining 
law lujan said in a statement this new agreement underscores 
our willingness to cooperate with citizen groups and the congress 
in seeing that the law is enforced consistently and effectively 
at the same time lujan said this settlement does not go 
beyond the laws requirements or compromise coal mine operators 
entitlement to due process of the law 
the agreement worked out in intense negotiating sessions 
beginning last september is aimed at creating a computer system 
that will accurately match previous violators of the law with 
applicants for new coal mining permits 
brent rushforth an attorney for save our cumberland mountains 
a principal plaintiff in the case told reporters this agreement 
goes further than ever before to assure that the information is 
accurate and that permits issued to violators can be suspended 
it doesnt go beyond the law it implements the law 
rushforth said 
filed in 1980 the suit arose out of the conviction of many 
residents of the coal mining regions of appalachia that strip 
mining laws were going unenforced 
an initial settlement was reached in 1981 after a court order 
directed the interior department to install a computer system to 
match past violators with new coal mining applicants 
critics complained some strip mine operators found to have 
violated the law simply changed the name of their companies and 
applied for a new permit at another location 
many such operators were failing to comply with requirements 
that the land be restored after the mining was completed the 
critics said 
installation of the computer system did not end complaints 
environmentalists contended the system proved wholly ineffective 
in preventing the issuance of new permits to past violators 
early last year the save our cumberland mountains organization 
sought to have a judge hold the interior department in contempt of 
court for allegedly failing to comply with the earlier court order 
that it strictly enforce the surface mining law 
</TEXT>
