<TEXT>
phyllis pelts workday is consumed by the grim 
realities of the ghetto the evicted family the girl who goes 
hungry the boy whose mother was murdered its part of life as a 
school nurse 
only minutes and miles away chuck ruders day on the 51st floor 
of the sleek sears tower is devoted to the fast pace and steady 
pressures of retail and finance its part of life in the fortune 
500 
little children and big business rich and poor two worlds 
seemingly destined to remain apart instead theyve united in an 
experiment in which corporate americas money muscle and 
management are being used to develop a desperately needed product 
academic success in the inner city 
the corporatecommunity schools of america is a tuitionfree 
academy created guided and financed by united airlines baxter 
international sears quaker oats mcdonalds and other 
chicagoarea powerhouses that donate dollars and sense to matters 
ranging from purchasing to personnel 
we must manage our schools as we manage our major corporations 
with accountability responsibility skilled talented paid 
people said school founder joe kellman if there was a profit 
motive is there any doubt ibm general motors and sears roebuck 
would be in the school business 
if you try to run major city school systems with volunteers 
that have no skill get no money and have no time then you get 
what youve got bankrupt systems he said 
big city education is a billiondollar business kellman says 
so who better to oversee it than experienced executives such as 
ruder from sears hes among seven corporate board members eight 
others are area residents or educators 
such partnerships arent new americas corporations have poured 
millions into education programs ranging from adoptaschool 
systems to guaranteed jobs organizers say this is different 
theyre supporting and assisting were building said bud 
kraus assistant to the chairman and chief executive officer at 
baxter a medical and hospital supply company 
the 1yearold private academy in predominantly black 
lawndale one of chicagos poorest neighborhoods is designed to be 
a lab to find ways to teach innercity children then duplicate the 
process in urban areas nationwide 
were looking to influence change in the system not educate 
300 kids kraus said 
the schools small size and independence set it apart unlike 
urban systems there are no powerful unions no tangled 
bureaucracies no crumbling buildings teachers salaries are 10 
percent to 15 percent higher 
as far as duplicating this in chicago i cant see how you can 
do it with prevailing resources said robert saddler deputy 
school superintendent and a board member of the corporate school 
still he said i dont think you have to replicate it on a 
mass scale to gain from it 
chicagos schools are doing their own experimenting with a 
reform plan establishing local councils in each of some 600 
schools giving parents major decisionmaking powers 
kellman thinks success will be limited considering 68 percent 
of chicagos 409000 public school students live in poverty the 
underclass will never manage their schools he said theyre 
having trouble managing their lives 
kellman concedes hes no educator he quit school after eighth 
grade to join his fathers glass business and now runs the 100 
million corporation 
but the 70yearold philanthropist knows business and hes 
devoted to lawndale his childhood home today its in trouble 
more than half lawndales residents get public aid more than a 
third of the housing is substandard recent studies found a murder 
rate six times the national average infant mortality almost three 
times as great 
if you walk into a typical class and ask a group of children 
how many know someone whos been shot hit by a car in jail 
or been killed virtually all the hands go up said primus 
mootry the schools project director who grew up in the area 
despite such brutal surroundings educators hope to prove these 
children can learn as well as those raised in affluence 
we do not accept any of the stereotypes that might travel 
with the neighborhood the school is situated in said teacher 
kathy irwin we do not put numbers on their heads in terms of iq 
some say there are social or biological limits we reject that 
the example were setting is that educating children in the 
inner city is not only possible but the children deserve it 
said principal elaine mosley 
to smooth the way the school has taken special steps 
classes for example are held yearround to minimize exposure 
to street life the building is open from 7 am to 7 pm to 
accommodate working parents preschool takes children as young as 
2 and high school equivalency degree programs are offered 
each room has a teacher and an aide there are no grades and 
children up to age 9 are grouped in twoyear clusters an idea that 
appeals to elaine finley whose two sons and daughter are pupils 
theyre learning at their own speed public school would 
have pushed them aside she said theyre active participants 
in learning in public school they would sit back behind a desk all 
day 
mrs pelt cuts red tape working with dozens of social service 
agencies she weighs children helps them get eyeglasses makes 
dental appointments supplies gloves accompanies parents to doctor 
visits and even allows them to do their laundry at the school 
the role of the school is everything that needs to be done to 
enhance learning she said 
money helps more than 28 million has been invested mostly by 
55 corporations providing annual contributions ranging up to 
150000 
the 5200 annual perpupil cost compared with 4624 in 
chicago will drop as enrollment increases from the current 200 to 
the 300 maximum kraus said all pupils are chosen by lottery 
businesses also provide resources sears for example donated 
carpeting air conditioners and cabinets but just as vital is 
whitecollar wisdom 
there are parts of the school that are much like a business 
personnel practice and policies for instance said ruder sears 
vice president of corporate public affairs 
still there are skeptics 
business leaders dont have the magic answer to education 
problems said don moore director of designs for change a group 
involved in chicagos school reform im just as content to see 
the manager of a store or a bus driver or a policeman on one of 
these councils he said 
moore also wonders how long are these corporations willing to 
put up this much money the history of these kinds of efforts 
is they fall on hard times after awhile 
school officials say its too early to gauge success but 
kellman predicts that at the end of three years pupils test 
scores will be better than their public school counterparts 
mootry said the school already has helped by bringing movers and 
shakers to lawndale 
they see the families he said they realize its not just 
a bunch of poor drugcrazed underclass folks but people struggling 
to make their lives better its drawing attention to the plight of 
the community its bringing some hope 
</TEXT>
