ford motor co ltd workers voted by nearly 32 to 
accept a 102 percent pay increase averting a nationwide strike 
union leaders said wednesday 
final returns showed that 59 percent of those voting went 
against their union leaders recommendation and accepted the 
improved offer they will get a 102 percent raise in the first 
year and a minimum of 8 percent or a choice of 25 percent above 
inflation in the second year 
the vote took place tuesday and wednesday 
most of the 32000 workers at the us companys 22 british 
plants earn an average of 374 a week 
union leaders rejected the offer last week and sought agreement 
from the workers to start striking with the last shift on friday 
the ford pay negotiations are considered a bellwether for 
britains manufacturing industry 
a higher settlement there would have encouraged other pay 
demands further undermining prime minister margaret thatchers 
battle to cut britains high inflation rate of nearly 8 percent 
as it is the ford deal is likely to mean more doubledigit pay 
demands the engineering union the biggest in the country 
immediately announced it considered 102 percent a benchmark 
for raises throughout industry 
a spokesman for the ford unions who wasnt identified in 
accordance with british practice said members accepted the 
proposal because it was quite a good offer 
it was always our aim to get our members a pay settlement in 
double figures and that we did he added 
