lower interest rates and production schedules 
could help make half of the nations financially troubled auto 
dealers profitable by years end according to the incoming 
president of the nations largest dealer group 
the national automobile dealers association which represents 
about 20000 us car and truck dealers has said for the past year 
that about half of its members either were losing money or just 
breaking even 
dealers have slashed vehicle orders from manufacturers trimmed 
advertising spending and shrunk their inventories to cut costs now 
its time for the government and manufacturers to do their part 
nada presidentelect ray green said tuesday 
i think it is a possibility this year we could look for an 
upturn if interest rates would drop to 9 percent and if the 
automakers would cut production to the rate of sales green said 
in a telephone interview from nada headquarters in suburban 
washington dc 
some economists have urged the federal reserve to lower the 
discount rate the interest it charges on loans to banks that in 
turn could encourage declines in openmarket interest rates 
possibly leading to a cut in the prime lending rate charged by 
banks now 10 percent 
banks use the prime for setting lending rates on some car loans 
and on a range of other consumer and business lending 
if the things happen that im talking about it could move 
easily to 75 percent profitable dealers by the end of the year 
said green it doesnt take much per car in expense or profit to 
change that considerably 
outgoing nada president ron tonkin and other organization 
officials blame the tough times for dealers on high interest rates 
and ambitious production schedules which forced manufacturers to 
stick incentives on their new cars to help clear jammed dealer lots 
that limited dealers ability to get a fair return on their 
investment tonkin has said and has shriveled their profits 
green said that on average dealers nationwide are losing money 
on new car sales and trying to make it up with profits from used 
cars service and parts operations 
green who begins his oneyear term as nada president next month 
at the organizations convention in las vegas hsa been a member of 
the nadas board of directors for eight years 
he got into the automotive industry in 1952 when he joined 
general motors acceptance corp as a field representative in des 
moines iowa two years later he became a salesman at a 
chevroletbuickcadillac dealership in iowa city 
green later became a general manager of a dealership in 
monmouth ill a business he bought in 1958 green now runs green 
holding co inc of jacksonville ill which owns four dealerships 
in central illinois holding seven franchises 
if the automobile manufacturers in north america are not 
making money and if the auto dealers are not making money selling 
new cars theres something not working out there green said 
its going to have to be a different arrangement 
