<TEXT>
ibm and siemens ag the german electronics 
giant said wednesday they would jointly develop a new generation 
of computer memory chips 
under the agreement the two companies will work on developing a 
64millionbit dynamic random access memory chip or dram 
the largestcapacity chip now on the market holds 4 million bits 
of information that chip was first introduced commercially by 
international business machines corp last year 
ibm and siemens also have independent efforts under way to 
develop 16millionbit chips which would be the next generation 
after the 4millionbit chip 
a bit is the smallest unit of information used by a computer 
because of the way chips are constructed advances in capacity 
usually take place in intervals of four times greater capacity than 
the previous generation 
development of the 64millionbit or 64 megabit chip will take 
place at ibms east fishkill ny semiconductor center and will 
use the resources of ibms essex junction vt facility and 
siemens munich research center the companies said in a statement 
each company will share equally in development costs the 
companies said manufacturing would be done individually by siemens 
and ibm said ibm spokesman paul bergevin 
ibm the worlds largest chip producer uses all the chips it 
makes in its own products it said it has no plans to sell the 
64millionbit chips on the open market 
the goal of the joint venture is to have a worldstandard 
64millionbit dram ready for commercial introduction in the 
mid1990s the companies said 
the strengths of the two firms complement one another and 
increase the probability that world leadership in memory chip 
technology will be maintained the companies said 
the companies did not disclose what they expect to invest in the 
venture bergevin said 
he said the joint venture was proposed to reduce the overall 
costs each firm would have had to bear individually 
he said it will be the first time ibm has jointly developed a 
computer chip although it has joint ventures in other areas for 
example ibm and siemens jointly operate the rolm telephone 
business 
one industry analyst said the announcement is not surprising 
the cost of development runs into the many millions of 
dollars each generation gets to be that much more expensive 
said millard h phelps of the san francisco investment firm 
hambrecht amp quist 
he said siemens which is known for its basic research is not a 
direct competitor of ibm 
as computer chips become more complex and more circuits are 
packed onto the silicon wafers the traditional method of making 
them using photolithography techniques with visible light to etch 
the electronic circuits is no longer practical phelps said 
probably at the 64 megabit level you cant do it that way 
he said and instead may require the use of xrays or electron 
beams for the etching 
theyre really having to break a lot of physics barriers 
getting to that level he said thats why they had to get 
somebody with basic research involved 
phelps said other companies known to be working on 64 megabit 
chips include texas instruments inc and a number of japanese 
companies including hitachi nec and matsushita 
</TEXT>
