<TEXT>
the upward spiral that carried the stock markets 
of the world to new highs through much of the 1980s now seems to be 
threatening to transform itself into a vicious cycle in the other 
direction 
and the catchphrase global investing suddenly no longer 
conjures up the heady images it once evoked in the minds of wall 
street brokers and their customers 
the new sequence that has unsettled so many investors and 
business planners played out in typical fashion wednesday 
share prices in the tokyo stock market which has been under 
intermittent pressure because of rising interest rates in japan 
posted a sharp loss driving the bellwether nikkei index of 225 
issues down 59904 points to 3677898 
as the business day shifted to europe stocks also dropped in 
london in selling attributed both to the decline in japan and fears 
of a shaky session in new york 
then trading began on wall street with a burst of selling that 
seemed preordained by what happened earlier in foreign financial 
centers 
the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell about 60 points in 
early trading on top of a loss of nearly 195 points over the past 
three weeks before staging a partial recovery to finish at 
260450 down 1082 on the day 
at the same time interest rates on us government securities 
continued their recent rise which was touched off by tightening 
monetary conditions abroad 
no matter what the federal reserves intentions for the domestic 
economy many analysts fear us interest rates will be forced 
higher just to stay competitive with higher yields on securities 
available to investors in the far east and europe 
that worry was reinforced tuesday when a government sale of 
40year bonds to finance a rescue plan for troubled thrift 
institutions drew a very chilly reception from investors 
at the extreme some observers worry the next noteworthy 
export to the united states from japan could be not a car or a 
stereo system but a recession aggravated by high borrowing costs 
however a sizeable optimistic contingent in the financial world 
maintains that events arent likely to reach that stage 
world markets toppled in domino fashion during the crash of 
1987 these observers recall but they started coming back strong 
within a matter of months paced by an especially brisk recovery in 
japan 
this time some suggest the us bond market could take a 
leading role in stabilizing the situation 
the more anemic the us economy gets analysts say the greater 
the appeal of treasury bonds might become if only because they 
represent a haven from default risk 
only a few weeks ago interest in us bonds was widespread 
based on an exclusive focus on the weak us economy observed 
robert barbera economist at shearson lehman hutton inc we do 
not expect further bond market deterioration 
should american bonds need a boost furthermore some analysts 
still believe they could get it from the federal reserve which 
