bankamerica corp chairman aw tom 
clausen reportedly is stepping down from the nations 
fourthlargest banking concern following a turnaround that moved 
the company from financial turmoil to record profits 
the san francisco examiner said the 66yearold clausens 
retirement and his successor would be announced before the banks 
annual meeting on may 24 bankamerica spokesman peter magnani 
declined comment wednesday about the report which was attributed 
to unidentified bank sources 
under clausen bankamerica rebounded from three years of huge 
financial losses with a restructuring that saw thousands of 
employees laid off its headquarters building and other major 
assets sold and its business refocused 
it also thwarted unwanted takeover overtures from rival first 
interstate bancorp in an oftenbitter struggle to remain 
independent 
the bank has made a tremendous recovery of health said 
dan williams a bank analyst with sutro and co of san francisco 
it may be that he clausen figures the time to go out is 
when youre on top 
clausen son of a small newspaper publisher from hamilton ill 
joined bankamerica as a 185aweek clerk counting cash in a vault 
in 1949 after he was graduated from the university of minnesota law 
school 
clausen worked his way up to chief executive by 1970 and during 
his tenure bankamerica quadrupled in size he left in 1981 to 
become president of the world bank in washington 
san franciscobased bankamerica the holding company for bank of 
america suffered three years of huge losses starting in 1985 much 
of its problems were blamed on losses from bad loans to developing 
nations and on real estate and farm loans in the united states 
in 1986 it eliminated its common stock dividend for the first 
time since the depression bankamerica once the largest banking 
concern in the country fell behind other giants such as citicorp 
and chase manhattan corp on the basis of assets 
some banking experts blamed much of bankamericas problems on 
clausen contending he contributed to many of its difficulties 
before leaving in 1981 with such moves as decentralization of its 
lending operations 
but clausen claimed the bank had lost the confidence of 
customers its board staff and shareholders because of 
overpromising and underperforming management of which he was 
not a part 
clausen returned as chairman in 1986 replacing ousted boy 
wonder samuel armacost who had earned the nickname clausens 
clone under armacost bankamerica was rocked by almost 6 
billion in loan losses and the battle with first interstate 
if we are given the time we will return our bank to its 
position of preeminence clausen pledged on his return the 
restructuring program will work i am absolutely confident 
about our strategy 
bankamerica sold assets including its world headquarters in san 
francisco for 660 million and its charles schwab discount 
brokerage subsidiary it cut expenses laid off 9000 employees and 
expanded hours while experiencing strong growth in domestic 
consumer and residential mortgage loans 
last february bank of america restored its common stock 
dividend last week the company reported 1989 earnings were up 52 
percent from a year earlier to 11 billion the biggest annual 
profit in its 86yearhistory it currently ranks fourth among bank 
holding companies with 829 billion in assets 
candidates seen as likely to succeed clausen include richard 
rosenberg 59 vice chairman of the board of bankamerica corp or 
frank newman 47 vice chairman and chief financial officer for 
bankamerica both worked previously for wells fargo amp co 
rosenberg was with wells for 22 years leaving a job there as 
vice chairman he also worked as vice chairman for crocker bank and 
was chief operating officer of seafirst corp newman spent 13 years 
with wells fargo working as executive vice president and chief 
financial officer before coming to bankamerica 
