the minnesota supercomputer center said 
tuesday it will install international business machine corps most 
powerful computer as part of a 55 million partnership expected to 
influence design of the next generation of ibm supercomputers 
using an ibm 3090 supercomputer with 12 interconnected 
processing units and with a memory capacity of more than five 
billion characters of information the supercomputer center will 
explore new ways to connect even more advanced supercomputers the 
center and ibm said in a joint statement 
ibm is funding about half the cost of the project according to 
the statement 
our partnership with ibm brings us the new capacity and 
challenge we need to maintain msc as a worldclass facility said 
john m sell chief operating officer and president of the 
minnesota supercomputer center 
under the agreement the supercomputer center will join ibm as a 
development partner and will use ibm supercomputing equipment in 
projects the center manages for its scientific and engineering 
customers sell said engineers at the center will be devising 
software with applications for all sorts of industries 
also the center will join the ibm information network and will 
provide aix services to ibm customers who use the network 
according to the statement 
aix is an operating system designed to make supercomputers 
advanced workstations and other data processing equipment operate 
in an environment that can handle numbers of users who want to 
perform many computing tasks simultaneously 
the minnesota supercomputer center is a private corporation 
owned jointly by the university of minnesota and the university of 
minnesota foundation 
