<TEXT>
the nations top securities regulator wednesday 
called on congress to remove legal and regulatory barriers so the 
united states could meet increasing competition in world financial 
markets 
securities and exchange commission chairman richard c breeden 
said the strength of japan as a financial center and the removal of 
european trade barriers in 1992 would give us capital markets 
their first real challenge 
breeden just back from three days of meetings in japan said 
securities professionals there told him the united states is 
regarded as the source of innovation and creativity in financial 
products 
we have to recognize that here at home and get rid of some of 
the legal and regulatory barriers breeden said at a meeting of 
the securities regulation institute 
breeden said the european economic communitys single market 
would mean standardized disclosure and takeover rules for companies 
and no barriers to banks engaging in the securities business as in 
the united states 
among other steps breeden called on congress to remove barriers 
to stock market trading of hybrid securities that have elements 
of futures 
a federal court recently banned trading of a stockindex future 
on the philadelphia and american stock exchange because of 
restrictions limiting such products to commodities exchanges 
if you can find one smidgen of futurity then that product 
becomes unlawful on stock exchanges breeden said that sets up 
the prospect that all products will have to go to the courthouse 
before going to investors 
similar securities are available to investors on the london and 
toronto stock exchanges he said 
breeden also said the united states should eliminate barriers 
under the glasssteagall act to allow banks to enter the securities 
business make takeover laws parallel in all states and remove 
barriers to interstate banking 
breeden also supported lowering barriers to foreign investment 
to make it harder for other countries to keep out us investors 
and companies 
along those lines he said japanese officials indicated they 
would allow foreign mutual funds into their countrys 500 billion 
investment trust business now limited to 14 japanese companies 
we believe the us mutual funds are the finest in the 
world breeden told reporters we would like to see them in 
japanese markets particularly the retail markets 
at a separate session former sec chairman david s ruder 
challenged the commission to become more active and farsighted in 
pushing for laws reforming the securities industry 
ruder who presided over the sec during two tumultuous years 
that included the october 1987 stock market crash and wall streets 
insider trading scandals called for a major study of securities 
industry reforms such as one undertaken in 1962 
there should be a study not only of volatility but of 
littleknown problems in the industry and we need to assess 
whether the crazyquilt regulation we have in the us over the 
banking and securities industries is the right one ruder said 
but breeden said there is too little time to undertake such a 
study which he said would take years 
id like to see congress and the administration get on with 
the task of reforming the securities market he said 
congress this session is considering a series of bills on market 
reform including the possibility of placing responsibility for 
regulating the nations stock and futures markets under one body 
ruder said he believes congress would be forced to reevaluate 
scrapping the glasssteagall act to allow banks to underwrite 
securities 
our financial institutions are going to be at a severe 
competitive disadvantage in the world if they cannot engage in 
banking and securities transactions at the same time he said 
