<DOCNO> AP900124-0306 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a group that includes four big california 
utilities unveiled an energy conservation plan wednesday aimed at 
saving hundreds of millions of dollars a year by paying people to 
buy more efficient homes and appliances and allowing stockholders 
to benefit from energy savings 
the plan by a coalition of businesses consumer advocates and 
environmentalists is intended to save fuel clean the air and 
ultimately lower costs for consumers 
by offering customers more incentives to use energy more 
efficiently we can help them reduce their energy costs and we can 
avoid or postpone having to build new power plants said virgil 
rose a vice president of pacific gas amp electric co one of four 
major utilities taking part in the plan 
utilities would be paying people to use less of their 
product observed ralph cavanagh of the natural resources defense 
council 
the plan calls for giving money to builders to encourage 
construction of homes and offices with better insulation and 
energysaving heating and cooling systems giving rebates to 
customers for buying energysaving appliances and financing free 
or lowcost home improvements for lowincome and elderly residents 
there was little incentive for utilities to make those 
investments in the late 1980s with fuel supplies abundant and oil 
and gas prices dropping utility conservation programs dropped 
sharply spending at pgampe dropped from 138 million in 1985 to 81 
million in 1988 and at san diego gas amp electric co from 178 
million in 1983 to 29 million in 1989 
the result has been increased home energy use more pollution 
and a greater depletion of resources 
the new plan set in motion by the state public utilities 
commission last july will be defined more fully in march when the 
four utilities pgampe sdgampe southern california edison and 
southern california gas submit formal proposals to the commission 
although elements of the plan have been used elsewhere in the 
country the size of the four utilities give their effort added 
importance 
pgampe and southern california edison are the nations two largest 
utilities in terms of sales the four utilities together serve at 
least three quarters of californias population cavanagh said 
others joining in the conservation plan included groups of 
developers small power producers water agencies the pucs 
consumer staff and the consumer group toward utility rate 
normalization 
the 82page proposal calls for 2638 million in conservation 
spending by the four utilities this year and 300 million in 1991 
those are no higher than mid1980s spending levels taking 
inflation into account but they are substantial increases over the 
totals of 153 million in 1988 and 1713 million in 1989 
the report said utilities should have fuel savings worth at 
least twice the added investment cost the utilities primarily burn 
domestically produced oil and gas in addition the report said 
similar programs in other states have estimated the benefits from 
environmental improvement as being worth 15 percent to 25 percent 
of the value of fuel savings 
customers though initially paying higher rates to subsidize the 
programs should get most of the savings through lower utility 
bills in the long run the report said 
the major incentive for utilities however is that some of the 
savings would go to stockholders under pgampes proposal for 
example 30 percent of the estimated fuel savings from most of 
programs and 5 percent of the costs of lowincome assistance would 
be given to stockholders 
the possibility of increased earnings can encourage utility 
management to search actively for new energyefficiency 
opportunities and to implement the programs effectively the 
report said summarizing the views of those who favor incentives 
the report also quoted opponents as saying the incentives were 
unnecessary would increase rates and were no substitute for puc 
regulation 
half or more of all spending would be on incentives for 
energyefficient new buildings 
utilities also are proposing a variety of individual programs 
pgampe wants to offer customers rebates of 50 and 100 for buying 
refrigerators that exceed federal efficiency standards by 10 or 15 
percent edison is proposing a design competition with 2500 
prizes for energyefficient buildings 
publicly owned utilities like the sacramento municipal utility 
district are not covered by the plan but the state energy 
commission said it would pursue conservation policies with them as 
well 
</TEXT>
