<TEXT>
great northern nekoosa corp the target 
of a hostile takeover offer reported a 39 percent drop in net 
income in the fourth quarter partly because of the cost of fending 
off the bid 
net income was 52 million or 92 cents a share compared to 
858 million or 156 a share in the last quarter of 1988 great 
northern said tuesday 
the norwalkbased paper company said its earnings per share were 
reduced by 33 cents because of the 38 billion offer made late 
last year by georgiapacific corp a forest products company in 
atlanta 
great northern is fighting georgiapacific using antitakeover 
provisions in its bylaws and an antitrust suit in connecticut 
chairman william r laidig also attributed the decline to a 
general downturn in the paper industry due to overcapacity 
business conditions changed around midyear when increasing 
paper capacity began to affect the supplydemand balance in many of 
our markets he said generally prices for most of our 
products had been relatively stable the first half of the year but 
weakened modestly in the third quarter and continued to weaken in 
the fourth 
great northern said fourthquarter sales fell 1 percent to 934 
million from 9441 million a year earlier shipments of pulp 
paper and containerboard from the companys mills fell 277 percent 
in the fourth quarter because of harsh weather at the companys 
southern mills 
net income for the year fell 6 percent to 321 million or 578 
a share from 3417 million or 621 a share in 1988 sales rose 
8 percent to 39 billion from 36 billion in 1988 
the outlook is a tough call because most of our markets are 
becoming more competitive laidig said our performance in 1990 
will depend on the strength of the us economy and the growth in 
demand for our products 
