<TEXT>
mexico will be removed from a list of 
countries accused of failing to provide adequate safeguards for 
intellectual property rights us trade representative carla hills 
said wednesday 
the mexican government has announced it will send its congress a 
package of proposed changes to improve the protection of patents 
and copyrights for companies doing business in mexico 
that follows action taken by the government earlier this month 
to draft new regulations aimed at reforming the countrys licensing 
and patent system 
the mexican government has demonstrated its firm belief in the 
need to protect intellectual property rights hills said in a 
statement announcing the action 
i want to encourage these developments and work toward a 
partnership across the rio grande that will provide a solid 
foundation for economic growth and expansion 
earlier commerce secretary robert mosbacher called mexicos 
actions a very important step the last big block to the forward 
movement of investment in mexico has been removed 
in may hills put mexico and seven other nations on a priority 
watch list saying the administration believed they were the worst 
offenders in failing to provide adequate protection of intellectual 
property rights 
negotiations under a section of us trade law known as special 
301 have been conducted with all eight nations in an effort to 
improve patent and copyright protections 
the eight countries on the original list were mexico brazil 
china india saudi arabia south korea taiwan and thailand 
taiwan korea and saudi arabia were moved to a secondary watch list 
in november because of progress in negotiations but mexico is the 
first country to be removed 
</TEXT>
