<DOCNO> AP900124-0309 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
ual corps three employee unions on wednesday 
proposed the acquisition of 75 percent of the airline companys 
stock by all employees leaving the remaining 25 percent in the 
publics hands 
in a letter to the companys board of directors united 
airlines pilots flight attendants and machinists said they were 
prepared to negotiate as a group for the acquisition of stock 
through one or more employee stock ownership plans or esops 
the employees offered wage concessions and longterm contracts 
in return 
we are unified as never before in our view that majority 
ownership of the company is the only acceptable means to resolve 
the issues that plague united the letter concluded 
uals board of directors is scheduled to meet thursday and had 
been planning to consider a recapitalization urged on the 
chicagobased company by one of its largest shareholders the 
coniston partners investment group holder of an 118 percent stake 
but keith gollust one of conistons principals said late 
wednesday that he and his partners were really pleased at the 
new development and were backing away from their insistence on a 
recapitalization to boost the value of ual shares 
we have always favored an employee buyout as an alternative 
gollust said in a telephone interview from his new york office 
we think this is a great step forward 
gollust said a recapitalization which likely would involve new 
borrowing by ual to make a payout to shareholders ought to 
remain as a backup alternative 
joe hopkins spokesman for ual the parent company of united 
declined comment on the esop proposal 
an esop typically buys stock with borrowed money and pays it 
back over a number of years with dividends on the shares 
the ual employees letter offered no specifics on how they plan 
to finance their proposed purchase of 17 million of uals 226 
million shares which would cost about 27 billion at wednesdays 
closing stock price of 16150 
officials of the three unions did not return phone calls 
airlines analyst samuel buttrick of kidder peabody amp co said 
the apparent harmony among uals unions and their willingness to 
take paycuts were a positive sign but the notable lack of 
specifics on structure and financing indicates that only minimal 
progess has been made on an ultimate resolution 
in return for a majority stake in the company the employees 
said they were prepared to make significant investments 
including an acceptance of lower wages under 5year contracts 
the investments including the contributions of nonunion 
employees would total about 300 million in the first year and 2 
billion over the life of the contracts the union group said 
the letter did not describe the proposed investments or specify 
how the unions proposed to divide the stock among uals four 
employee groups 
our objective is to form a unique partnership among the 
company and all employees that will permit the company to 
immediately return to the position of the worlds best airline 
and to grow and prosper into the future read the letter 
the letter was signed by john peterpaul vice president of the 
machinists union frederick c dubinsky chairman of the united 
chapter of the air line pilots association and diana robertson 
president of the united chapter of the association of flight 
attendants 
uals stock climbed 6 to close at 16150 wednesday in new york 
stock exchange trading 
ual directors are under pressure from coniston partners a new 
yorkbased investment group with 118 percent of uals stock to 
quickly approve a transaction that will boost shareholder value 
coniston urged uals directors to explore a recapitalization 
after management and the pilots failed to pull together a buyout 
offer by jan 8 the date of the last board meeting 
at that meeting the board directed its financial adviser first 
boston corp to explore the merits of a recapitalization and come 
up with a proposal for thursdays meeting 
but the board also said it reamined open to buyout proposals 
both the pilots and the united chapter of the association of 
flight attendants have expressed strong opposition to any 
recapitalization that would increase the indebtedness of the 
nations secondlargest airline and allow for anything less than 
majority ownership of the company by its workers 
the machinists opposed a previous buyout attempt led by uals 
management and pilots which caused lenders to balk and the 675 
billion buyout bid to fail on oct 13 
the ual buyout saga began last august when los angeles 
billionaire marvin davis made an unsolicited offer of 200 a share 
or 432 billion for the company 
the failed pilotmanagement bid was for 300 a share 
</TEXT>
